{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gove, Michael}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]]\n[[Category:BBC newsreaders and journalists]]\n[[Category:British Christian Zionists]]\n[[Category:British Christians]]\n[[Category:British Secretaries of State for Education]]\n[[Category:British Secretaries of State for the Environment]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Critics of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Daily Mail journalists]]\n[[Category:Lord Chancellors of Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Neoconservatism]]\n[[Category:People educated at Robert Gordon's College]]\n[[Category:People from Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Oxford Union]]\n[[Category:Scottish adoptees]]\n[[Category:Scottish columnists]]\n[[Category:Scottish journalists]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for Justice]]\n[[Category:The Times people]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Michael Gove\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Rt Hon Michael Gove MP crop 2.jpg\n| caption = Gove in 2020\n| office = [[Minister for the Cabinet Office]]\n| primeminister = [[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start = 13 February 2020\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Oliver Dowden]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start1 = 24 July 2019\n| term_end1 = \n| predecessor1 = [[David Lidington]]\n| successor1 = \n| office2 = [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start2 = 11 June 2017\n| term_end2 = 24 July 2019\n| predecessor2 = [[Andrea Leadsom]]\n| successor2 = [[Theresa Villiers]]\n| office3 = [[Secretary of State for Justice]]<br />[[Lord Chancellor|Lord High Chancellor of Great Britain]]\n| primeminister3 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start3 = 9 May 2015\n| term_end3 = 13 July 2016\n| predecessor3 = [[Chris Grayling]]\n| successor3 = [[Liz Truss]]\n| office4 = [[Chief Whip|Chief Whip of the House of Commons]]<br />[[Parliamentary Secretary to the Treasury]]\n| primeminister4 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start4 = 15 July 2014\n| term_end4 = 9 May 2015\n| predecessor4 = [[George Young, Baron Young of Cookham|George Young]]\n| successor4 = [[Mark Harper]]\n| office5 = [[Secretary of State for Education]]\n| primeminister5 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start5 = 12 May 2010\n| term_end5 = 15 July 2014\n| predecessor5 = [[Ed Balls]]\n| successor5 = [[Nicky Morgan]]\n| office6 = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education|Shadow Secretary of State for Children, Schools and Families]]\n| leader6 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start6 = 2 July 2007\n| term_end6 = 11 May 2010\n| predecessor6 = [[David Willetts]]\n| successor6 = [[Ed Balls]]\n| office7 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Surrey Heath (UK Parliament constituency)|Surrey Heath]]\n| term_start7 = 5 May 2005\n| term_end7 = \n| predecessor7 = [[Nick Hawkins]]\n| successor7 = \n| majority7 = 18,349 (31.3%)\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1967|8|26|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Aberdeen]],<ref>Bennett, Owen (2019). ''Michael Gove: A Man in a Hurry'', p. 1. Biteback Publishing, London. {{ISBN|9781785904400}}.</ref> Scotland\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| otherparty = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] (1983)\n| spouse = {{Marriage|[[Sarah Vine]]|2001}}\n| children = 2\n| education = [[Robert Gordon's College]]\n| alma_mater = [[Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]] (M.A.)\n| module = {{Listen\n|embed            = yes\n|title            = Gove's voice\n|filename         = Michael Gove BBC Radio4 Start the Week 30 December 2013 b03mcmwx.flac\n|type             = speech\n|description      = from the BBC programme ''[[Start the Week]]'', 30 December 2013<ref name=\"BBC-b03mcmwx\">{{cite episode |title=Michael Gove |series=Start the Week |serieslink=Start the Week |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03mcmwx |accessdate=18 January 2014 |station=BBC Radio 4 |date=30 December 2013}}</ref>}}\n| birth_name = Graeme Andrew Logan\n}}\n\n'''Michael Andrew Gove''' ({{IPAc-en|g|o:|v|}}; born '''Graeme Andrew Logan''';<ref name=\":1\" /> 26 August 1967) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician who has been [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]] since July 2019 and [[Minister for the Cabinet Office]] since February 2020. He has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Surrey Heath (UK Parliament constituency)|Surrey Heath]] since 2005. Gove served in the [[First Cameron ministry|Cameron governments]] as [[Secretary of State for Education]] from 2010 to 2014<ref>{{cite news |title=Cabinet reshuffle: David Cameron's new line-up |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-19475248 |accessdate=27 October 2013 |date=4 September 2012 |work=BBC News}}</ref>  and [[Secretary of State for Justice]] from 2015 to 2016, and in the [[Second May ministry|second May government]] as [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]. He has twice run to become [[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|Leader of the Conservative Party]], in [[2016 Conservative Party leadership election|2016]] and [[2019 Conservative Party leadership election|2019]], finishing in third place on both occasions.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48711077 |title=Johnson and Hunt left in Tory leader race |work=BBC News |date=20 June 2019 |accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nGove began a career as an author and [[journalist]] for ''[[The Times]]'' before entering the [[House of Commons]].<ref name=\"Sharman-Indy 2016a\">{{cite news |last=Sharman |first=Jon |date=15 January 2017 |title=Donald Trump gives first post-election UK interview to Michael Gove |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/donald-trump-first-interview-michael-gove-post-election-theresa-may-meeting-a7528136.html |quote=Mr Gove returned to ''The Times'' last year as a columnist, having worked there up until his election in 2005. |accessdate=16 January 2016 |newspaper=The Independent |location=London}}</ref> He was appointed to the [[Shadow Cabinet of David Cameron|Shadow Cabinet]] by [[David Cameron]] in 2007 as [[Shadow Cabinet (UK)|Shadow Secretary of State for Children, Schools and Families]]. As Education Secretary, the [[National Association of Head Teachers]]<ref name=bbc18may13>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-22558756 |accessdate=27 October 2013 |title=Michael Gove heckled at head teachers' conference in Birmingham |date=18 May 2013 |work=BBC News}}</ref> [[Association of Teachers and Lecturers]], [[National Union of Teachers]] and [[NASUWT]] passed motions of no confidence in Gove's policies at their conferences in 2013.<ref name=gran2apr13>{{cite news |last=Shepherd |first=Jessica |date=2 April 2013 |title= NUT passes unanimous vote of no confidence in Michael Gove |url= https://www.theguardian.com/education/2013/apr/02/nut-no-confidence-michael-gove |accessdate=27 October 2013 |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London}}</ref> \n\nIn [[2014 United Kingdom Cabinet reshuffle|a 2014 Cabinet reshuffle]], Gove was moved to the post of [[Chief Whip#United Kingdom|Chief Whip]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28306405 |title=Michael Gove moved to chief whip in cabinet reshuffle |work=BBC News |date=15 July 2014 |accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC Online 2014\">{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28302487 |title= Michael Gove move not a demotion, says David Cameron |work=BBC News |date=15 July 2014 |accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref> Following the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 election]], Gove was promoted to the [[Great Officer of State|office]] of [[Secretary of State for Justice|Justice Secretary]] and [[Lord Chancellor]]. In 2016, Gove played a major role in the UK's [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|referendum on EU membership]] as the co-convenor of [[Vote Leave]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/eu-referendum-michael-goves-full-statement-on-why-he-is-backing-brexit-a6886221.html |title=Michael Gove's 1,500-word essay on why he wants Britain to leave the EU |work=The Independent |location= London |date=20 February 2016}}</ref> Along with fellow Conservative MP [[Boris Johnson]], Gove was seen as one of the most prominent figures of the Vote Leave campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://graphics.wsj.com/embeddable-carousel/?slug=ukpolitics0626|title=WSJ.com|website=graphics.wsj.com|access-date=4 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 June 2016, Gove, who was campaign manager for [[Boris Johnson]]'s leadership bid to become Prime Minister, withdrew his support on the morning that Johnson was due to declare, and announced his own candidacy in the [[2016 Conservative Party leadership election|leadership election]]. Following [[Theresa May]]\u2019s appointment as Prime Minister he was sacked from the Cabinet; however, following the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] he was appointed [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment Secretary]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Rachel |last=Roberts |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/michael-gove-cabinet-reshuffle-environment-secretary-latest-a7785036.html |title=Cabinet reshuffle: Michael Gove returns to Cabinet as Environment Secretary |newspaper=The Independent |location= London |date=11 June 2017 |accessdate=6 August 2017}}</ref> \n\nHe launched another Conservative Party leadership bid in 2019 although eventually came third behind Johnson and [[Jeremy Hunt]]. Upon the appointment of Johnson as Prime Minister, Gove was appointed [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]], with responsibilities including preparations for a [[no-deal Brexit]]. He took on the additional role of [[Minister for the Cabinet Office]] in the cabinet reshuffle post-Brexit.\n\n==Early life==\nGraeme Logan was born on 26 August 1967.<ref>{{cite news|title=POLITICO London Playbook, presented by BP: We have lift off \u2014 Gove is the drug I'm thinking of \u2014 How to spend \u00a310 billion|url=https://www.politico.eu/newsletter/london-playbook/politico-london-playbook-presented-by-bp-we-have-lift-off-gove-is-the-drug-im-thinking-of-how-to-spend-10-billion/|accessdate=10 June 2019|publisher=Politico|date=10 June 2019}}</ref> His biological mother, whom he originally believed to have been an unmarried Edinburgh student, was in fact a 23-year-old cookery demonstrator.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/adopted-goves-past-detailed-in-book-590s0gvvn|title=Adopted Gove's past detailed in book|last=Chief\u00a0Political\u00a0Correspondent|first=Kate Devlin|date=11 June 2019|work=The Times|accessdate=16 June 2019|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> Gove regarded his birthplace as [[Edinburgh]] until it was revealed in a biography in 2019 that he was born in a maternity hospital in Fonthill Road, [[Aberdeen]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Michael Gove: A Man in a Hurry|last=Bennett|first=Owen|publisher=Biteback Publishing|year=2019|isbn=9781785904400|location=United Kingdom|pages=1}}</ref>\n\nLogan was put into care soon after he was born. At the age of four months he was adopted by a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]-supporting couple in [[Aberdeen]], Ernest and Christine Gove, by whom he was brought up.<ref name=\"SuppLab\">Johnston, Simon (16 May 2010).[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/7730573/Teenage-Michael-Gove-supported-Labour.html \"Teenage Michael Gove supported Labour\".] ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]''.</ref> After he joined the Gove family, Logan's name was changed to Michael Andrew Gove.<ref name=\":1\" /> His adoptive father, Ernest, ran a [[fish processing]] business and his adoptive mother, Christine, was a [[lab assistant]] at the [[University of Aberdeen]], before working at the Aberdeen School for the Deaf.<ref name=\"michaelgove.com\">{{cite web|title=The Rt Hon. Profile: Michael Gove|url=http://www.michaelgove.com/biography|accessdate=27 October 2013|publisher=michaelgove.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130707063046/http://www.michaelgove.com/biography|archivedate=7 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn Aberdeen, Gove was educated at two state schools (Sunnybank Primary School and Kittybrewster Primary School), and later, on the recommendation of his Primary school teacher, he sat the entrance exam for the independent [[Robert Gordon's College]]. Later, as he entered the [[sixth form]] he had to apply for a scholarship as his family fell on difficult economic circumstances.<ref name=\"SuppLab\" /> In October 2012, he wrote an apology letter to his former French teacher for misbehaving in class.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gove apologises to his former French teacher|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-20034101|accessdate=30 August 2013|work=BBC News|date=23 October 2012}}</ref> From 1985 to 1988 he read English at [[Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]], graduating with an [[British undergraduate degree classification|upper second]].<ref name=\"MGperLMH\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lmh.ox.ac.uk/Alumni/Prominent-alumni.aspx |title=Prominent Alumni ... Government and Public Service |work=Lady Margaret Hall Oxford |accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"newsnightreview\" /> \n\nDuring his first year, he met future Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] and helped him become elected [[President of the Oxford Union]].<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.cityam.com/friends-then-rivals-boris-johnson-has-the-last-laugh-over-michael-gove/ |title=Friends, then rivals: Boris Johnson has the last laugh over Michael Gove |date=20 June 2019 |website=City AM |location= London |access-date=7 August 2019}}</ref> In an interview with [[Andrew Gimson]], Gove remarked that at Oxford, Johnson was \"quite the most brilliant [[extempore]] speaker of his generation.\"<ref>{{Citation|chapter=Cult of the SSRI|date=2006|pages=[https://archive.org/details/cultofpharmacolo0000degr/page/34 34\u201363]|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=9780822338819|doi=10.1215/9780822388197-002|title=The Cult of Pharmacology|url=https://archive.org/details/cultofpharmacolo0000degr/page/34}}</ref> Gove was elected President of the Oxford Union a year after Johnson.<ref>Class list published in ''The Times'', 29 July 1988; p. 33</ref>\n\n== Journalism career ==\nGove became a trainee reporter at ''[[The Press and Journal (Scotland)|The Press and Journal]]'' in Aberdeen, where he spent several months on strike in the 1989\u20131990 dispute over union recognition and representation.<ref name=\"People_2010-03-21\">{{cite news|url=http://www.people.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/2010/03/21/picture-emerges-of-tory-strike-basher-michael-gove-on-the-picket-line-during-his-own-walkout-93463-22127004|title=Picture emerges of Tory strike basher Michael Gove on the picket line during his OWN walkout|newspaper=[[The People]]|date=21 March 2010|accessdate=29 May 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120330083039/http://www.people.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/2010/03/21/picture-emerges-of-tory-strike-basher-michael-gove-on-the-picket-line-during-his-own-walkout-93463-22127004|archivedate=30 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe joined ''[[The Times]]'' in 1996 as a [[leader writer]] and assumed posts as its comment editor, news editor, Saturday editor and assistant editor. He has also written a weekly column on politics and current affairs for the newspaper and contributed to ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]'', ''[[Prospect (magazine)|Prospect]]'' magazine and ''[[The Spectator]]''. He remains on good terms with [[Rupert Murdoch]],<ref name=MatNorm>{{Cite news|last=Norman|first=Matthew|date=29 February 2012|title=Let us never forget the stench of this rank corruption|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/matthew-norman/matthew-norman-let-us-never-forget-the-stench-of-this-rank-corruption-7462447.html|accessdate= 27 October 2013|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Karnitschnig|first=Matthew|url=http://www.politico.eu/blogs/spence-on-media/2016/06/brexit-eu-referendum-rupert-murdochs-support-for-boris-johnson-comes-with-a-warning|title=Rupert Murdoch's support for Boris Johnson comes with a warning|publisher=Politico.eu|accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref> whom Gove described in evidence before the [[Leveson Inquiry]] as \"one of the most impressive and significant figures of the last 50 years\".<ref name=\"FT interview\"/> He wrote a sympathetic biography of [[Michael Portillo]] and a highly critical study of the [[Northern Ireland peace process]] (''The Price of Peace''), where he compared the [[Good Friday Agreement]] to appeasement of the Nazis in the 1930s.<ref name=\"newsnightreview\">{{cite news|title=Michael Gove|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/newsnight/review/panel/2043945.stm|accessdate=27 October 2013|work=Newsnight Review|publisher=BBC News |date=22 April 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The Price of Peace|last=Gove|first=Michael|publisher=Centre for Policy Studies|year=2000|isbn=1-903219-15-9|location=London|pages=ii}}</ref><ref>https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/uk/michael-gove-a-fanatic-who-would-damage-peace-process-1.2710224</ref>\n\nHe has worked for the BBC's ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]'' programme, ''[[On the Record (BBC TV series)|On The Record]]'', [[Scottish Television]] and the Channel 4 current affairs programme ''[[A Stab in the Dark (TV series)|A Stab in the Dark]]'', alongside [[David Baddiel]] and [[Tracey MacLeod]], and was a regular panellist on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[The Moral Maze]]'' and ''[[Newsnight Review]]'' on [[BBC Two]].<ref name=\"michaelgove.com\"/><ref name=\"MacLeod 2016\">{{cite web|last1=MacLeod|first1=Tracey|title=The TV show I made with Michael Gove still gives me nightmares|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/commentisfree/2016/jul/05/the-tv-show-i-made-with-michael-gove-still-gives-me-nightmares?CMP=twt_a-culture_b-gdnculture|website=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Aitkenhead\">{{cite web|last1=Aitkenhead|first1=Decca|author-link=Decca Aitkenhead|title=Michael Gove: the next Tory leader?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/oct/05/michael-gove-next-tory-leader|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=5 October 2012|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\n[[File:MichaelGove.jpg|thumb|Gove outside the Palace of Westminster, December 2008]]\nHe briefly joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] in 1983 in [[Aberdeen]], but has stated that by the time he left to go to [[Oxford University]] he was a Conservative.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}} Gove joined the [[Oxford University Conservative Association]] and was secretary of [[Aberdeen South (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen South]] [[Young Conservatives (UK)|Young Conservatives]].<ref>{{Cite news |last= Settle |first= Michael |date=3 October 2005 |title= Rollercoaster ride for leadership contenders |url= http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/rollercoaster-ride-for-leadership-contenders-tory-conference-1.41383 |accessdate=27 October 2013 |newspaper= [[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]  |location= Glasgow}}</ref> He helped to write speeches for Cabinet and Shadow Cabinet ministers, including [[Peter Lilley]] and [[Michael Howard]].<ref>{{cite web |title= ZCC Business Breakfast with Michael Gove MP |url= http://www.zcc.org.uk/site/node/52 |accessdate= 27 October 2013 |publisher= Zionist Central Council of Greater Manchester |year= 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131029200636/http://www.zcc.org.uk/site/node/52 |archivedate= 29 October 2013 }}</ref> When applying for a job at the [[Conservative Research Department]] he was told he was \"insufficiently political\" and \"insufficiently Conservative\", so he turned to journalism.<ref>{{Cite news |last= Burkeman |first= Oliver |date=31 January 2005 |title= Clever move |url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/jan/31/pressandpublishing.politicsandthemedia |accessdate=27 October 2013 |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nGove had been{{when|date=October 2017}} chairman of [[Policy Exchange]], a conservative [[think tank]] launched in 2002.<ref>{{cite web | title= Michael Gove | url= http://whoknowswho.channel4.com/people/Michael_Gove | accessdate= 27 October 2013 | work= Who knows who | publisher= [[Channel 4]] | url-status=dead | archiveurl= https://archive.is/20130119152938/http://whoknowswho.channel4.com/people/Michael_Gove | archivedate= 19 January 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last= Beckett | first= Andy | date= 26 September 2008 | title= What can they be thinking? | url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/sep/26/thinktanks.conservatives | accessdate= 27 October 2013 | newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> He was involved in founding the right-leaning magazine ''[[Standpoint (magazine)|Standpoint]]'', to which he occasionally contributes.<ref>{{cite web | title= Writers A\u2013Z \u00bb Michael Gove | url= http://standpointmag.co.uk/writers/?showid=Michael%20Gove | accessdate= 27 October 2013 | publisher= standpointmag.co.uk | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161227092855/http://standpointmag.co.uk/writers/?showid=Michael%20Gove | archive-date= 27 December 2016 | url-status= dead }}</ref> Gove expressed admiration in late-February 2003 for [[Second Blair Ministry|New Labour]] [[UK Prime Minister|Prime Minister]] [[Tony Blair]] because of the way he was handling the crisis in [[Iraq]]: \"As a [[right-wing politics|right-wing]] polemicist, all I can say looking at Mr Blair now is, what's not to like?\" Blair, he thought, was \"behaving like a true [[Thatcherism|Thatcherite]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Gove|first=Michael|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/law/columnists/article2042633.ece|title=I can't fight my feelings any more: I love Tony|work=The Times|location=London|date=25 February 2003|accessdate=17 January 2017}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n=== Member of Parliament ===\n[[File:Michael Gove.jpg|thumb|left|Gove speaking at the Conservative Party \"Big Society, Not Big Government\" policy launch]]\nGove first entered the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] after the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]] having been elected as the Conservative Member of Parliament for [[Surrey Heath (UK Parliament constituency)|Surrey Heath]], after the sitting Conservative MP [[Nick Hawkins]] was deselected by the local Conservative Association.<ref>{{Cite news |last= Kite |first= Melissa |date= 27 June 2004 |title= Surrey Heath members believe that their money ought to be able to buy a future prime minister |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1465579/Surrey-Heath-members-believe-that-their-money-ought-to-be-able-to-buy-a-future-prime-minister.html |accessdate= 27 October 2013 |newspaper= The Sunday Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= Michael Gove: Electoral history and profile |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/person/9378/michael-gove |accessdate= 27 October 2013 |newspaper= The Guardian}}</ref> When [[David Cameron]] was first elected as [[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|Leader of the Conservative Party]] in December 2005, he appointed Gove as Shadow Housing Spokesman.<ref>{{Cite news |last= Jones |first= George |date=14 December 2005 |title= Cameron signals sensitivity on immigration |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1505436/Cameron-signals-sensitivity-on-immigration.html |accessdate=27 October 2012 |newspaper= The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> Gove is seen as part of an influential set of Conservatives, sometimes referred to as the [[Notting Hill Set]], which includes: former Prime Minister [[David Cameron]], former [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] [[George Osborne]], [[Edward Vaizey]], [[Nicholas Boles]] and [[Rachel Whetstone]].<ref>{{Cite news |title= Who are the Notting Hill Set? |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1511473/Who-are-the-Notting-Hill-Set.html |accessdate= 27 October 2013 |newspaper= The Daily Telegraph |date=26 February 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 July 2007, Gove was promoted to the [[Shadow Cabinet]] as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Children, Schools and Families]] (a newly created department set up by [[Gordon Brown]]), shadowing [[Ed Balls]]. Prior to the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], most of Gove's questions in Commons debates concerned children, schools and families, education, local government, council tax, foreign affairs, and the environment.<ref>{{cite web | title= Michael Gove, Conservative MP for Surrey Heath | url= https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/11858/michael_gove/surrey_heath | accessdate= 27 October 2013 | publisher= [[TheyWorkForYou]] }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, [[Michael Portillo]] backed Gove to be a serious contender in a future race for the Conservative Party leadership,<ref>{{cite news | title = Portillo: Gove 'serious candidate' as Tory leader | url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18549543 | accessdate= 27 October 2013 | work= BBC News | date= 22 June 2012 }}</ref> though Gove had said in an interview a few months before that \"I'm constitutionally incapable of it. There's a special extra quality you need that is indefinable, and I know I don't have it. There's an equanimity, an impermeability and a courage that you need. There are some things in life you know it's better not to try.\"<ref name = \"Standpoint interview\">{{Cite journal | last= Martin | first= Iain | title = Will Michael Gove Go All the Way to No 10? | url= http://standpointmag.co.uk/features-march-12-will-gove-go-all-the-way-to-no-10-iain-martin-michael-gove-conservatives-david-cameron | accessdate= 27 October 2013 | journal= [[Standpoint (magazine)|Standpoint]] | issue= March 2012 | date= 21 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\n=== Secretary of State for Education (2010\u20132014)===\n[[File:Michael Gove Minister.jpg|thumb|upright|Gove as Secretary of State for Education, c. 2012]]\nWith the formation of the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|Conservative-Liberal Democrat coalition government]] following the hung parliament after the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], Gove became [[Secretary of State for Education]]. His first moves included reorganising his department,<ref>{{cite news |title= Department for Education returns in coalition rebrand |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8679749.stm |accessdate=27 October 2013 |work=BBC News |date=13 May 2010 }}</ref> announcing plans to allow schools rated as \"outstanding\" by [[Ofsted]] to become [[Academy (English school)|academies]],<ref>{{cite news |last= Harrison |first= Angela |date=26 May 2010 |title= Schools are promised an academies 'revolution' |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10159448 |accessdate= 27 October 2013 |work= BBC News}}</ref> and cutting the previous government's school-building programme.<ref>{{cite news |last= Richardson |first= Hannah |date=5 July 2010 |title= School buildings scheme scrapped |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10514113 |accessdate=27 October 2013 |work=BBC News}}</ref> He apologised, however, when the list of terminated school-building projects he had released was found to be inaccurate; the list was reannounced several times before it was finally accurately published.<ref>{{cite news |title= Gove apologises over school building list errors |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10538754 |accessdate= 27 October 2013 |work= BBC News |date=7 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, Gove said that [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] had failed in their attempt to break the link between [[social class]] and school achievement despite spending billions of pounds: quoting research, he indicated that by the age of six years, children of low ability from affluent homes were still out-performing brighter children from poorer backgrounds. At a [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] [[Education Select Committee]] he said that this separation of achievement grew larger throughout pupils' school careers, stating, \"In effect, rich thick kids do better than poor clever children when they arrive at school [and] the situation as they go through gets worse\".<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/educationnews/7914719/Rich-thick-kids-do-better-at-school-says-Gove.html |first=Graeme |last=Paton |title= 'Rich thick kids' do better at school, says Gove |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=28 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==== Building Schools for the Future and school capital projects ====\nIn February 2011, a [[judicial review]] deemed Gove's decision to axe [[Building Schools for the Future]] (BSF) projects in six local authority areas was unlawful as he had failed to consult before imposing the cuts.<ref name=JR>{{cite news |last= Richardson |first= Hannah |date=11 February 2011 |title= Councils defeat government over school buildings |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-12429152 |accessdate=27 October 2013 |work= BBC News}}</ref> The judge also said that, in five of the cases, the failure was \"so unfair as to amount to an abuse of power\" and that \"however pressing the economic problems, there was no overriding public interest which precluded consultation or justifies the lack of any consultation\".<ref name=JR/> The councils' response was that the government would have to reconsider but the government said it had won the case on the substantial issues.<ref name=JR/> The judge made clear that, contrary to the councils' position, they could not expect that their projects would be funded.<ref name=JR/>\n\nIn March 2011, Gove was criticised for not understanding the importance of school architecture and having misrepresented the cost.<ref name=guard>{{Cite news |last= Moore |first= Rowan |date=6 March 2011 |title= Architects do matter, Mr Gove |url= https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2011/mar/06/michael-gove-architecture-in-schools |accessdate=27 October 2013 |newspaper= [[The Observer]]}}</ref> In February 2011, he gave \"not-quite-true information to Parliament\" by saying that one individual made \u00a31,000,000 in one year when the true figure was \u00a3700,000 for five advisers at different times over a four-year period.<ref name=guard/> He told a [[Free school (England)|Free Schools]] conference that \"no one in this room is here to make architects richer\" and specifically mentioned architect [[Richard Rogers]].<ref>{{Cite news |last= Fulcher |first= Merlin |date=2 February 2011 |title= Gove: Richard Rogers won't design your school |url= http://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/news/daily-news/gove-richard-rogers-wont-design-your-school/8610768.article |accessdate=27 October 2013 |newspaper= [[Architects' Journal]] }}</ref>\n\n==== Exam and curriculum reforms ====\nGove's views on exam systems became clear in December 2014 after the release of archive papers from 1986. GCSEs were the brainchild of Sir [[Keith Joseph]]. [[Margaret Thatcher]], believing they lacked rigour, fiercely opposed them. However, opposition to the new exams from the teaching unions persuaded her to introduce them immediately, purely so as not to appear weak. Although Gove had sought but failed to replace them, his special advisor, [[Dominic Cummings]], described the 1986 decision as catastrophic, leading to a collapse in the integrity of the exam system.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/politics/article4309304.ece |title=Thatcher introduced GCSEs to spite the teaching unions |newspaper=The Times |last= Sanderson|first= David |date=30 December 2014 |accessdate=30 January 2015 |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2010 Conservative Party Conference, Gove announced that the [[National Curriculum (England, Wales and Northern Ireland)|primary and secondary-school national curricula]] for England would be restructured, and that study of authors such as [[Byron]], [[Keats]], [[Jane Austen]], [[Dickens]] and [[Thomas Hardy]] would be reinstated in English lessons as part of a plan to improve children's grasp of [[English literature]] and [[English language|language]]. [[Academy (English school)|Academies]] are not required to follow the national curriculum, and so would not be affected by the reforms. Children who fail to write coherently and grammatically, and who are weak in spelling, would be penalised under new examinations. Historian [[Simon Schama]] would give advice to government to ensure that pupils learnt Britain's \"island story\". Standards in mathematics and science would also be strengthened. He said that this was needed because [[left-wing politics|left-wing]] ideologues had undermined education. Theirs was the view, he thought, that schools \"shouldn't be doing anything so old-fashioned as passing on knowledge, requiring children to work hard, or immersing them in anything like dates in history or times tables in mathematics. These ideologues may have been inspired by generous ideals but the result of their approach has been countless children condemned to a prison house of ignorance\".<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/educationnews/8043872/Conservative-Part-Conference-schoolchildren-ignorant-of-the-past-says-Gove.html |title=Conservative Party Conference: schoolchildren 'ignorant of the past', says Gove |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=5 October 2010 |accessdate=12 May 2011 |first=Graeme |last=Paton}}</ref>\n\nIn a November 2010 [[white paper]], Gove declared reforms would include the compulsory study of foreign languages up to the age of sixteen years, a shake-up of league tables in which schools are ranked higher for the number of pupils taking GCSEs<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-12914964 |work=BBC News |title= 'Gaming' the school league tables? |date=31 March 2011}}</ref> in five core subjects (English, mathematics, science, a language and one of the humanities), and the introduction of targets for primary schools. It proposed that trainee teachers should spend more time in the classroom, teacher training applicants should be more rigorously tested \u2014 including tests of character and emotional intelligence \u2014 and sponsorships for former troops to retrain as teachers to improve discipline. It also said teachers would receive guidance on how to search pupils for more items, including mobile phones and pornography, and when they can use force.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/educationnews/8155995/Education-White-Paper-key-points.html |title=Education White Paper: Key points |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=24 November 2010 |accessdate=12 May 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:Michael Gove at Chantry High School.jpg|thumb|right|Gove, as Education Secretary, at Chantry High School, [[Ipswich]]]]\nIn April 2011, Gove criticised schools for not studying pre-twentieth century classics and blamed \"England's constricted and unreformed exam system\" for failing to encourage children to read. Gove also blamed an \"anti-knowledge culture\" for reducing achievement and said children benefited when expectations were set higher.<ref name=mocking>{{Cite news |last= Paton |first= Graeme |date=1 April 2011 |title= Michael Gove: schools failing to promote the classics|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/educationnews/8419770/Michael-Gove-schools-failing-to-promote-the-classics.html|accessdate=27 October 2013|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> In June 2011, his \"ignorance of science\" was criticised{{by whom|date=October 2017}} after he called for students to have \"a rooting in the basic scientific principles\" and by way of example assigned [[William Thomson, 1st Baron Kelvin|Lord Kelvin's]] [[laws of thermodynamics]] to Sir [[Isaac Newton]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Chivers|first=Tom|date=23 June 2011|title=Would you have confused Shakespeare and Dickens, Michael Gove|url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/tomchiversscience/100093493/would-you-have-confused-shakespeare-and-dickens-michael-gove|accessdate=14 January 2012|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' published leaked plans to scrap [[GCSE]] examinations, return to [[GCE Ordinary Level|O-level]] exams and allow less academic students to take alternative qualifications. The [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] claimed that the plans had not been discussed with the [[Nick Clegg|Deputy Prime Minister]] and were subsequently heavily criticised by some teachers, trade unions and Labour Party MPs;<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Garner|first1=Richard|last2= Wright|first2=Oliver|date=21 June 2012|title=Michael Gove faces criticism over GCSE axe in exam overhaul|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/michael-gove-faces-criticism-over-gcse-axe-in-exam-overhaul-7872863.html|accessdate=27 October 2013|newspaper= The Independent|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last1=Mulholland|first1=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne|last2=Watt|first2=Nick|date=21 June 2012|title=Michael Gove's plan to scrap GCSEs is ludicrous, say teaching union leaders|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2012/jun/21/michael-gove-gcses-teaching-union|accessdate=27 October 2013|newspaper=The Guardian |location= London}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Paton|first=Graeme|date=21 June 2012|title=Lib Dems vow to block Michael Gove's plan to axe GCSEs|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/educationnews/9347101/Lib-Dems-vow-to-block-Michael-Goves-plan-to-axe-GCSEs.html|accessdate=27 October 2013|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|location=London}}</ref> they had been discussed with the Prime Minister at Cabinet level, and a subsequent ''YouGov''/''Sunday Times'' [[opinion poll|poll]] suggested that the public supported this policy by a margin of 50% to 32%.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18547842|title=GCSE row: No 10 insists Cameron did know about Gove plan|work=BBC News|accessdate=25 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdn.yougov.com/cumulus_uploads/document/0w8gg3rki9/YG-Archives-Pol-ST-results-22-240612v2.pdf|publisher=YouGov|title=YouGov/''The Sunday Times'' Survey Results|date=22 June 2012}}</ref> They received praise from the then-[[Mayor of London]] [[Boris Johnson]], who said that he \"could be... singing a hymn of praises for my old chum Gove and his brilliant new Gove-levels.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Johnson|first=Boris|authorlink=Boris Johnson|date=22 June 2012|title=House of Lords reform: Nick Clegg's crazy plan is a pay day for has-beens and never-wozzers|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/columnists/borisjohnson/9353376/House-of-Lords-reform-Nick-Cleggs-crazy-plan-is-a-pay-day-for-has-beens-and-never-wozzers.html|accessdate=27 October 2013|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> The leaked documents also suggested that Gove was intending to create a single exam board to organise all exams, and to scrap the National Curriculum in its current form. However, there were \"rebukes\" from both the Welsh and Northern Ireland Education ministers who said it was important to communicate before making announcements on proposed changes to jointly owned qualifications.<ref>{{cite news |title= Wales and Northern Ireland rebuke on GCSEs announcement |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-19078094 |accessdate=27 October 2013 |work=BBC News |date=1 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013, shortly after the draft Programmes of Study for History in the national curriculum was released by the DfE,<ref>{{Cite news |last= Priestland |first= David|date=12 February 2013 |title= Michael Gove's new curriculum: what the experts say |url= https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/feb/12/round-table-draft-national-curriculum |accessdate=27 October 2013 |newspaper=The Guardian |display-authors=etal}}</ref> the representatives of the principal organisations for historians in the UK wrote to ''[[The Observer]]'' to register \"significant reservations\" about its contents and the way in which it had been devised. They described it as \"too narrowly and exclusively focused on British history\" and argued that structuring history teaching in a strictly chronological sequence meant that students would learn about pre-modern history only in the early stages of their studies.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=D'Avray|first1=David|last2=Eales|first2=Jackie|author2-link=Jacqueline Eales|last3=Fulbrook|first3=Mary|author3-link=Mary Fulbrook|last4= McLay|first4=Keith|last5=Mandler|first5=Peter|author5-link=Peter Mandler|last6=Scott|first6=Hamish|date=17 February 2013|title=Plan for history curriculum is too focused on Britain |url= https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2013/feb/16/history-curriculum-letters|newspaper=The Observer}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, 100 academics wrote an open letter arguing that Gove's curriculum placed too much emphasis upon memorisation of facts and rules over understanding, and would lead to more rote learning.<ref>{{Cite news |last= Bassey|first= Michael|date=20 March 2013|title= Letters: Gove will bury pupils in facts and rules|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/letters/letters-gove-will-bury-pupils-in-facts-and-rules-8540741.html|accessdate=21 October 2013|newspaper=The Independent|display-authors=etal}}</ref> Gove retorted that \"there is good academia and bad academia.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shepherd|first=Jessica|date=21 March 2013|title=Michael Gove labels professors critical of new curriculum as 'bad academia'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2013/mar/21/michael-gove-professors-new-national-curriculum|accessdate=21 October 2013|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> In response, one signatory to the letter opined that Gove suffered from a \"blinkered, almost messianic, self-belief, which appears to have continually ignored the expertise and wisdom of teachers, head-teachers, advisers and academics, whom he often claims to have consulted\",<ref>{{Cite news|last=Manning|first=Ralph|date=28 March 2013 |title=Letters: Gove ignores the real issues with the curriculum |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/letters/letters-gove-ignores-the-real-issues-with-the-curriculum-8551923.html|accessdate=21 October 2013|newspaper=The Independent}}</ref> A senior civil servant admitted that one of the most controversial parts of the proposed secondary curriculum had been written internally by the DfE, without any input from experts.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Stewart|first=William|date=12 April 2013|title=Gove's curriculum could be 'chaos', leaders warn|url=http://www.tes.co.uk/article.aspx?storycode=6328609|accessdate=21 October 2013|newspaper=Times Educational Supplement|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140127145839/http://www.tes.co.uk/article.aspx?storycode=6328609|archive-date=27 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn May, [[Simon Schama]], earlier mooted as a supporter of Gove's reforms of the history curriculum, delivered an excoriating speech in which he characterised the finalised proposals as \"insulting and offensive\" and \"pedantic and utopian\", accusing Gove of constructing a \"ridiculous shopping list\" of subjects. He urged the audience at the [[Hay Festival]]: \"Tell Michael Gove what you think of it. Let him know.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Furness |first=Hannah |date=30 May 2013 |title=Hay Festival 2013: Don't sign up to Gove's insulting curriculum, Schama urges |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/hay-festival/10090287/Hay-Festival-2013-Dont-sign-up-to-Goves-insulting-curriculum-Schama-urges.html |accessdate=15 October 2013 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> In June, leaked documents revealed that a member of the government's curriculum advisory group had described the reform process as having had \"a very chaotic feel. It's typical of government policy at the moment: they don't think things through very carefully, they don't listen to anyone and then just go ahead and rush into major changes.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last= Mansell |first= Warwick |date= 24 June 2013 |title= Curriculum experts say Gove's plans could lower standards |url= https://www.theguardian.com/education/2013/jun/24/national-curriculum-experts-criticise-government |accessdate= 21 October 2013 |newspaper= The Guardian}}</ref> In September, [[Robin Alexander]] said that the proposed reforms to the primary-level national curriculum were \"neo Victorian\", \"educationally inappropriate and pedagogically counter-productive\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Garner |first=Richard |date=24 September 2013 |title=Michael Gove creating 'neo Victorian' curriculum for primary schools, says professor who led massive review into sector |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/michael-gove-creating-neo-victorian-curriculum-for-primary-schools-says-professor-who-led-massive-review-into-sector-8837223.html |accessdate=21 October 2013 |newspaper=The Independent}}</ref> In October, almost 200 people, including: [[Carol Ann Duffy]], [[Melvin Burgess]] and [[Michael Rosen]], as well as academics from Oxford, Bristol and Newcastle universities signed a letter to ''[[The Times]]'' condemning Gove's reforms, warning of the \"enormous\" and negative risks they posed to children and their education.<ref>{{Cite news |date=1 October 2013 |title=Letters: Narrow test-based education 'harms children'|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/letters/article3883125.ece|newspaper=The Times|accessdate=1 October 2013|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nThat same month saw Oxford's head of admissions warn that the timetable for secondary-level reforms would \"just wreck the English education system.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Garner|first=Richard|date=15 October 2013|title=Government plans to overhaul GCSEs and A-levels at the same time will 'wreck' education, says Oxford University's head of admissions|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/student/news/government-plans-to-overhaul-gcses-and-alevels-at-the-same-time-will-wreck-education-says-oxford-universitys-head-of-admissions-8881992.html|accessdate=21 October 2013|newspaper=The Independent}}</ref>\n\n====2012 English GCSE results====\nIn September 2012, following the furore surrounding the downgrading of GCSE English results, he refused, during his answers to the Parliamentary Education Committee on 12 September, to instruct Ofqual to intervene, and attacked his Welsh counterpart as \"irresponsible and mistaken\" for ordering disputed GCSEs to be regraded.<ref>{{cite news|last=Coughlan|first=Sean|date=12 September 2012|title= Michael Gove attacks Welsh GCSE regrade|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-19569429|accessdate=27 October 2013|work=BBC News}}</ref> On 17 September he announced to the House of Commons an [[English Baccalaureate]] Certificate to replace GCSE, comprising English, Maths, Science, together with a Humanities subject and language, to be first examined in 2017. His plans to replace GCSE examinations with an English Baccalaureate were rejected by Parliament in February 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Planned switch from GCSEs to Baccalaureate in England 'abandoned'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-21363396|accessdate=27 October 2013|work=BBC News|date=7 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Education vouchers====\nAs Shadow Secretary of State for Children, Schools and Families, Gove advocated the introduction of a Swedish-style voucher system, whereby parents can choose where their child should be educated, with the state paying what they would have cost in a state-school. He has also advocated Swedish-style [[Free school (England)|free schools]], to be managed by parents and funded by the state,<ref>{{cite news |first=Jessica |last=Shepherd |url= https://www.theguardian.com/education/2010/mar/07/conservatives-lure-private-schools-state |title=Conservatives aim to lure private schools into state system |newspaper=The Guardian |date=7 March 2010 |accessdate=8 May 2010}}</ref> with the possibility that such schools may be allowed to be run on a for-profit model.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/may/29/michael-gove-open-state-schools-profit |accessdate=31 May 2012 |date=29 May 2012 |newspaper=The Guardian |first=Jeevan |last=Vasagar |title=Michael Gove open-minded over state schools being run for profit}}</ref>\n\n====Creationist schools====\nIn June 2012, Gove approved three [[Creationism|creationist]] schools, including Grindon Hall Christian School in [[City of Sunderland|Sunderland]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grindonhall.com|title=Grindon Hall Christian School|publisher=grindonhall.com|accessdate=5 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022170636/http://www.grindonhall.com/|archive-date=22 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> which opened in September 2012. This led to concerns about whether Department for Education (DfE) requirements not to teach [[creationism]] or [[intelligent design]] as science would be met.<ref name=creat>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2012/jul/17/creationist-groups-approval-free-schools?|title=Creationist groups win Michael Gove's approval to open free schools|last=Vasagar|first=Jeevan|newspaper=The Guardian|date=17 July 2012|accessdate=18 July 2012}}</ref> The other creationist schools included Exemplar-Newark Business Academy, whose previous application was rejected because of concerns over creationism, and a third school in [[Kent]]. Both schools said they would teach creationism in RE but not in Science.<ref name=creat/>\n\nThe [[British Humanist Association]] (BHA) said teaching creationism in any syllabus was unacceptable.<ref name=creat/> In 2014, Gove's department acceded to the BHA's campaign by banning creationism from being taught as science in state-funded English schools, including Academies and Free Schools, as well as introducing a requirement that such schools must teach evolution.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://humanism.org.uk/2014/06/18/victory-government-bans-existing-future-academies-free-schools-teaching-creationism-science|title=Government bans all existing and future Academies and Free Schools from teaching creationism as science|date=18 June 2014|accessdate=17 June 2015|publisher=British Humanist Association}}</ref>\n[[File:Michael Gove at Policy Exchange delivering his keynote speech 'The Importance of Teaching' (9679846486).jpg|thumb|Gove at [[Policy Exchange]] in 2013]]\n\n==== Children's homes scandal and data protection rules ====\nIn September 2013, news that the DfE did not maintain a register of children's homes in the UK came to light as a result of an article Gove wrote for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''. Gove asserted his prior ignorance and surprise that the department did not hold this information and claimed that \"Ofsted was prevented by 'data protection' rules, 'child protection' concerns and other bewildering regulations from sharing that data with us, or even with the police\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Gove|first=Michael|date=12 September 2013|title= I'm ending this scandal over children's care|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/children_shealth/10304696/Michael-Gove-Im-ending-this-scandal-over-childrens-care.html|accessdate=28 September 2013|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nGove's claim was refuted the same day by the Information Commissioner, [[Christopher Graham|Sir Christopher Graham]], who pointed out there was \"nothing\" in data protection legislation that prevents vulnerable young people from being properly protected in care homes. Graham noted that \"[t]his law covers information about people so it has no bearing on the disclosure of non-personal information like the location of care homes\", and said he would be writing to both Gove and [[Michael Wilshaw|Sir Michael Wilshaw]] about the matter.<ref>{{cite press release|last=Graham|first=Christopher|title=ICO responds to Michael Gove article in today's Daily Telegraph|url=http://www.ico.org.uk/news/latest_news/2013/ico-responds-to-michael-gove-article-daily-telegraph|publisher=Office of the Information Commissioner|accessdate=28 September 2013|date=13 September 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130917160049/http://www.ico.org.uk/news/latest_news/2013/ico-responds-to-michael-gove-article-daily-telegraph|archivedate=17 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== Social work training ====\nIn November 2013 Gove delivered a speech to the [[National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children|NSPCC]] in which he argued that [[social work]] training involved 'idealistic students being told that the individuals with whom they will work have been disempowered by society'. Gove held that students were being 'encouraged to see [service users] as victims of [[Social justice|social injustice]] whose fate is overwhelmingly decreed by the economic forces and inherent inequalities which scar our society'. Gove suggested that the intellectual demands of many social work courses should be raised. Gove explained that the training of social workers was of personal importance to him because his own life had been transformed by social workers as a result of his [[adoption]] at the age of four months old.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/getting-it-right-for-children-in-need-speech-to-the-nspcc|title=Secretary of State for Education Michael Gove delivers a speech on child protection|date=12 November 2013|website=www.gov.uk|accessdate=15 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-24904031|title=More child protection takeovers ahead, Gove hints|accessdate=15 January 2018|publisher=BBC|work=BBC News|date=12 November 2013|last1=Richardson|first1=Hannah}}</ref>\n\nWhile serving as Education Secretary, Gove asked Sir [[Martin Narey]], a former director general of prisons and chief executive of [[Barnardo's]], to conduct a review of social work education. Sir Martin  subsequently made 18 recommendations, which he said could be implemented at \"minimal cost\", for the reform of social work education. Sir Martin called for more emphasis to be placed on practical skills and suggested that some of the students recruited were not up to the job. Sir Martin found that course standards varied widely and called for tighter minimum entry standards and the standardisation of the teaching provided to social work students.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-26157066|title=Call to upgrade social work training|last=Harrison|first=Angela|date=13 February 2014|work=BBC News|accessdate=15 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Birmingham schools row====\nIn June 2014, a very public argument arose between the [[Home Office]] and Department for Education Ministers about responsibility for [[Operation Trojan Horse|alleged extremism in Birmingham schools]],<ref name=telegraph-20140604bb>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/benedictbrogan/100274682/theresa-may-is-angry-really-angry|title=Theresa May is angry. Really angry|last=Brogan|first= Benedict|newspaper=Daily Telegraph blogs|date=4 June 2014|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=telegraph-20140604ty>{{cite news |url= http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/tobyyoung/100274724/five-things-you-need-to-know-about-theresa-mays-row-with-michael-gove|title=Five things you need to know about Theresa May's row with Michael Gove|last=Young|first= Toby|newspaper=Daily Telegraph blogs|date=4 June 2014|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref> which required PM [[David Cameron]]'s intervention to resolve.<ref name=observer-20140607>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jun/07/cameron-gove-may-extremism-row|title=Furious Cameron slaps down Gove and May over 'Islamic extremism' row|last1=Helm|first1= Toby |last2=Boffey|first2= Daniel|last3=Mansell|first3= Warwick|newspaper=The Observer|date=7 June 2014|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Prime Minister asked Gove to apologise to Home Office [[Office for Security and Counter-Terrorism]] Head [[Charles Farr]] for briefings critical of him which appeared on ''[[The Times]]'' front page.<ref name=bbc-20140608>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-27750921|title=Michael Gove apologises over 'Trojan Horse' row with Theresa May|work=BBC News |date=8 June 2014|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Criticism from the teaching profession====\nGove was criticised by teachers unions for his attempts to overhaul British education. At the [[Association of Teachers and Lecturers]] (ATL) Annual Conference in March 2013 a motion of no-confidence in Gove was passed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Teachers Pass No Confidence Vote In Gove|url=http://news.sky.com/story/1069526/teachers-pass-no-confidence-vote-in-gove|accessdate=27 October 2013|publisher=[[Sky News]]|date=25 March 2013}}</ref> This was followed up the next month at the annual conference of the [[National Union of Teachers]] (NUT), who unanimously passed a vote of no confidence in Gove and called for his resignation.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/education/2013/apr/02/nut-no-confidence-michael-gove |title=NUT passes unanimous vote of no confidence in Michael Gove |last=Shepherd |first=Jessica |date=2 April 2013 |work=The Guardian |location= London |access-date=25 October 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThe audience at the NUT conference were told{{by whom|date=October 2017}} that Gove had \"lost the confidence of the teaching profession\", \"failed to conduct his duties in a manner befitting the head of a national education system\", and \"chosen to base policy on dogma, political rhetoric and his own limited experience of education.\"<ref name=\"gran2apr13\"/> Gove was further criticised at the May 2013 conference of the [[National Association of Head Teachers]] (NAHT), for what they claimed was a climate of bullying, fear and intimidation during his time as Education Secretary. The conference passed a vote of no confidence in his policies.<ref name=\"bbc18may13\"/>\n\nChanges to pay, pensions, and workloads were also controversial. The NUT and NASUWT staged strikes on a regional basis in October 2013,<ref>{{Cite news|date=5 September 2013|title=NUT and NASUWT announce teachers' plan to strike in October|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/educationnews/10288098/NUT-and-NASUWT-announce-teachers-plan-to-strike-in-October.html|accessdate=27 October 2013|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|agency=[[Press Association]]|date=17 October 2013|title=Thousands of schools affected as teachers strike over pay and conditions|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2013/oct/17/teachers-strike-pay-thousands-schools-nasuwt|accessdate=27 October 2013|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> although a national strike was averted.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Robinson|first=Sadie|date=25 October 2013|title=Teachers' unions pull back from national strike this year against Gove|url=http://www.socialistworker.co.uk/art/36704|accessdate=1 November 2013|newspaper=[[Socialist Worker]]|issue=2376}}</ref> After talks failed,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Paton|first=Graeme|date=6 November 2013|title=Michael Gove 'refusing to back down over teachers' strike'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/educationnews/10431430/Michael-Gove-refusing-to-back-down-over-teachers-strike.html|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Garner|first=Richard|date=26 December 2013|title=Teachers threaten more strikes as talks with Michael Gove stumble|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/teachers-threaten-more-strikes-as-talks-with-michael-gove-stumble-9026340.html|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref> strike action affecting 10,000 schools took place in March 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Saul|first=Heather|date=26 March 2014|title=Teachers' strike affects 10,000 schools|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/teachers-strike-affects-10000-schools-9216018.html|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Sarah Vine]], Gove's wife, accused [[socialists]] of sending their family \"vicious and aggressive\" death threats due to Gove's education reforms, and said she had considered moving with their two children to Italy as a result of these threats.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dathan|first1=Matt|title=Gove's wife Sarah Vine admits fears over hatred|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/education/article4097850.ece|work=The Times|date=23 May 2014|accessdate=17 January 2017|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Before the coalition government, in 2010, a [[YouGov]] poll of teachers' voting intentions found that 33% were Tory and 32% were Labour; four years later, a poll found that only 16% were Tory and 57% were Labour.<ref name=\"FT interview\"/>\n\n=== Chief Whip of the House of Commons (2014\u20132015) ===\nOn 15 July 2014, Gove's four-year stint in charge of the Department for Education came to an end when he was replaced as Secretary of State for Education by former Treasury Minister [[Nicky Morgan]] in a wide-ranging cabinet reshuffle. Gove was moved to the post of Government [[Chief Whip]],<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\" /> which was portrayed as a demotion by his detractors; Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] denied this was the case.<ref name=\"BBC Online 2014\" /> Gove told [[BBC News]] that he had mixed emotions about starting the new role, saying it was a privilege to become Chief Whip but that leaving the Department for Education was \"a wrench\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28319641 \"Michael Gove: 'It's a wrench but a privilege changing job'\"], BBC News, 15 July 2014; retrieved 16 July 2014.</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-politics-28306405/michael-gove-moved-to-chief-whip-in-cabinet-reshuffle |title=Gove moved to chief whip in reshuffle |website=BBC News |date=15 July 2014 |access-date=4 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/15/michael-gove-chief-whip-david-cameron-reshuffle-cabinet |title=Michael Gove demoted to chief whip as Cameron shows no sentimentality |last=Watt |first=Nicholas |date=15 July 2014 |work=The Guardian |access-date=3 September 2019| last2=Wintour |first2=Patrick}}</ref>\n\nThe position came with a \u00a330,000 pay cut, and a specific media role saw Gove on television and radio \"more than a traditional Chief Whip would be\".<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/10970261/Michael-Gove-was-prepping-for-Whips-role-for-days-his-wife-says.html |title=Michael Gove was prepping for Chief Whip role for days, says his wife |last=Graham |first=Georgia |date=16 July 2014 |access-date=4 September 2019 |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London }}</ref> He missed his first House of Commons vote in the new role, as explained by Shadow Commons Leader [[Angela Eagle]]; \"Gove not only lost his first vote but managed to get stuck in the toilet in the wrong lobby\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/michael-gove-gets-stuck-in-commons-toilet-on-first-day-in-new-job-as-chief-whip-9612203.html|title=Michael Gove 'gets stuck in Commons toilet' on first day in new|date=17 July 2014|website=The Independent |access-date=4 September 2019}}</ref> Gove remained in the post of Chief Whip until May 2015, when the role was taken over by [[Mark Harper]].\n\n=== Secretary of State for Justice (2015\u20132016)===\nAfter the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] promoted Gove as Lord Chancellor and Justice Secretary in his newly formed [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Michael Gove moves to justice in post-election reshuffle|date=10 May 2015|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2015-32679004|work=BBC News}}</ref> He was praised in December 2015 for scrapping the courts fee introduced by his predecessor, [[Chris Grayling]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/tax-on-justice-michael-gove-scraps-criminal-courts-charges-after-independent-campaign-a6758616.html |title=Tax on justice: Michael Gove scraps criminal courts charges after Independent campaign|date=3 December 2015|accessdate=4 December 2015|newspaper=The Independent|last=Dugan|first=Emily|last2=Wright|first2=Oliver}}</ref> The fee had been heavily criticised for, among other things, causing innocent people to plead guilty out of financial concerns.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/court-charges-could-put-pressure-on-defendants-to-plead-guilty-claim-judges-a6736906.html|title=Court charges could put pressure on defendants to plead guilty, claim judges|date=16 November 2015|newspaper=The Independent|last=Cooper|first=Charlie}}</ref> Gove removed the 12-book limit on prison books introduced by Grayling, arguing that books increased literacy and numeracy, skills needed for making prisoners a \"potential asset to society\". The move, effective from September 2015, was welcomed by Frances Cook of the [[Howard League for Penal Reform]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-33497581|title=Prisoner book restrictions scrapped by Michael Gove|work=BBC News|date=12 July 2015|accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref> Gove was also praised for his prominent role in scrapping a British bid for a Saudi prison contract.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/oct/13/uk-ditches-plan-to-bid-for-saudi-arabia-prisons-contract|title=UK ditches plan to bid for \u00a35.9m Saudi Arabia prisons contract|date=13 October 2015|accessdate=6 December 2015|newspaper=The Guardian|last=Watt|first=Nicholas|last2=Travis|first2=Alan}}</ref>\n\nWithin three months of his taking office, the Criminal Bar Association voted to stop taking new work in protest at Gove's insistence that they work for lower fees.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bowcott|first=Owen|date=15 July 2015|title=Barristers vote to join solicitors' legal aid protest|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2015/jul/15/barristers-vote-to-join-solicitors-legal-aid-protest|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> The CBA subsequently praised his \"courage\" in reversing the proposed cuts.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Barrett |first1=David |title=Legal aid cuts reversed by Justice Secretary Michael Gove |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/law-and-order/12128011/Legal-aid-cuts-reversed-by-Justice-Secretary-Michael-Gove.html |accessdate=28 January 2016 |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=12 June 2016}}</ref> On 14 July 2016 Gove was removed from the position of Justice Secretary by the new Prime Minister, [[Theresa May]].<ref name=\"sacking\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36785814|title=Theresa May's cabinet: Who's in and who's out?|work=BBC News|accessdate=14 July 2016|date=14 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== European Union membership referendum (2016)===\nGove described his decision to [[Vote Leave|campaign for Britain to leave the EU]] in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|EU referendum]] as \"the most difficult decision of my political life\".<ref name=\"bbcbrexit\">{{cite news|title=UK 'better off' out of EU \u2013 Michael Gove|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35617843|accessdate=4 June 2016|publisher=BBC}}</ref> He and his family spent Christmas with the Camerons at [[Chequers]] where, according to [[Craig Oliver (British journalist)|Craig Oliver]], Cameron got the impression that Gove would support remaining in the EU.{{sfn|Oliver|2016|p=52}} He argued Britain would be \"freer, fairer and better off\" for leaving.<ref name=\"bbcbrexit\" /> When in an interview it was claimed that there was no expert opinion to support this, Gove remarked that \"the people of this country have had enough of experts from organisations with acronyms saying they know what is best and getting it consistently wrong.\"<ref name=Newsweek>{{cite news |url=http://europe.newsweek.com/michael-gove-sky-news-brexit-economics-imf-466365|title=Michael Gove: I'm 'Glad' Economic Bodies Don't Back Brexit}}</ref> However, interviewer [[Faisal Islam]] interrupted Gove after the word \"experts\",<ref name=GuGoveInt>{{cite AV media\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/live/2016/jun/03/eu-referendum-michael-gove-questioned-on-sky-news|title=Michael Gove questioned on Sky news|time=1:30}}</ref> causing some sources to report that he had made a general statement that \"the people... have had enough of experts\".<ref name=FT>{{cite news |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/3be49734-29cb-11e6-83e4-abc22d5d108c.html#axzz4G50gEbvD|title=Britain has had enough of experts, says Gove|first=Michael |last=Gove |newspaper=[[Financial Times]] |date=3 June 2016 |accessdate=1 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016 Gove repeated the controversial [[Vote Leave]] claim that an additional \u00a3350&nbsp;million a week could be spent on the NHS when Britain left the EU but said it was up to the Government to decide how to spend it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/dec/28/brexit-campaigner-michael-gove-defends-nhs-funding-pledge|title=Brexit campaigner Michael Gove defends NHS funding pledge |first=Rowena |last=Mason |work=The Guardian|date=28 December 2016|accessdate=28 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn his memoir ''[[For the Record (book)|For the Record]]'' [[David Cameron]] described Gove during this period as \"mendacious\", adding: \"One quality shone through, disloyalty. Disloyalty to me and, later, disloyalty to Boris [Johnson]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/15/five-things-we-learned-from-david-cameron-memoir-boris-johnson-michael-gove-referendum|title=\nFive things we learned from David Cameron's memoir|last=Davies|first=Caroline|date=15 September 2019|accessdate=17 September 2019|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nIn the aftermath of the referendum, Gove was accused by [[Nick Clegg]] of being the source of a claim by [[The Sun (United Kingdom)|''The Sun'']] that Queen [[Elizabeth II]] made comments supportive of Brexit in a private lunch at [[Windsor Castle]]. Clegg told a BBC documentary that Gove \"obviously communicated it \u2013 well, I know he did\".<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36986977 |title=Gove 'behind Queen backs Brexit story' |date=7 August 2016|work=BBC News|access-date=11 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/nick-clegg-claims-michael-gove-leaked-queen-backs-brexit-story-to-the-sun-a7177151.html |title=Nick Clegg thinks Gove leaked the Queen's views on Brexit |date=7 August 2016 |website=The Independent |url-status=live |access-date=11 October 2019}}</ref> Gove declined to deny leaking the Queen's comments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35793773|title=Gove 'did not brief' Queen Brexit story |date=12 March 2016|work=BBC News |access-date=11 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/queen-elizabeth-II/12189540/Gove-faces-Queen-Brexit-questions.html |title=Michael Gove to face questions over 'Queen Brexit' row as minister is implicated in leak |last=Dominiczak |first=Peter |date=9 March 2016 |work=The Telegraph |access-date=11 October 2019 |location= London}}</ref>\n\n===Conservative Party leadership candidate (2016)===\nAfter [[David Cameron]] announced his intention to resign as Prime Minister, with his successor now likely to be in office by September 2016, Gove was not a candidate, having said in the past that he had no interest in becoming Prime Minister.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/05/06/michael-gove-rules-out-running-for-tory-leader-and-says-his-frie|title=Michael Gove rules out running for Tory leader and says his friendship with David Cameron will survive the referendum |accessdate=30 June 2016|newspaper=The Telegraph |date=6 May 2016 |last1=Dominiczak |first1=Peter }}</ref> Instead, he was seen as a strong, highly influential supporter of [[Boris Johnson]] for that role. In a move that surprised most political analysts, Gove withdrew his support for Johnson on 30 June 2016, hours before the deadline, without any previous notice to Johnson and announced his own candidacy in the [[2016 Conservative Party leadership election|leadership election]]. Subsequently, Johnson declined to run.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36672591|title=Boris Johnson rules himself out of Conservative leader race|accessdate=30 June 2016|work=BBC News|date=30 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' opined that Gove's actions in undermining Johnson's leadership aspirations constituted \"the most spectacular political assassination in a generation\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Swinford|first1=Steven|last2=Hope|first2=Christopher|last3=Dominiczak|first3=Peter|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/30/boris-johnsons-allies-accuse-michael-gove-of-systematic-and-calc|title=Boris Johnson's allies accuse Michael Gove of 'systematic and calculated plot' to destroy his leadership hopes|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=30 June 2016|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref> while ''[[The Guardian]]'' labelled it as a \"Machiavellian move\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mason|first1=Rowena|last2=Stewart|first2=Heather|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/30/goves-thunderbolt-boris-johnson-tory-morning|title=Gove's thunderbolt and Boris's breaking point: a shocking Tory morning|work=The Guardian|date=30 June 2015|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nGove said: \"I wanted to help build a team behind [[Boris Johnson]] so that a politician who argued for leaving the European Union could lead us to a better future. But I have come, reluctantly, to the conclusion that Boris cannot provide the leadership or build the team for the task ahead. I have, therefore, decided to put my name forward for the leadership. I want there to be an open and positive debate about the path the country will now take. Whatever the verdict of that debate I will respect it. In the next few days I will lay out my plan for the United Kingdom which I hope can provide unity and change.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Cowburn|first=Ashley|date=30 June 2016|title=Michael Gove's statement on running for Tory leadership against Boris Johnson|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/michael-goves-statement-on-running-for-tory-leadership-against-boris-johnson-read-it-in-full-a7110596.html|newspaper=The Independent|location=London|accessdate=30 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nBy 5 July 2016, Gove was in third place in the [[2016 Conservative Party leadership election]]  behind [[Theresa May]] and [[Andrea Leadsom]]; the latter had gained an endorsement from [[Boris Johnson]]. Some political analysts predicted that Gove might quit the race if he was unable to beat Leadsom in the first round of voting.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wilkinson |first=Michael |date=5 July 2016 |title=Conservative leadership election: Theresa May surges ahead as Tory MPs suggest Michael Gove could quit the race|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/05/boris-johnson-backs-andrea-leadsom-tory-mps-vote-leadership-race|newspaper=The Telegraph|location=London|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref> Later that day, it was announced that Theresa May won the first round of voting, with support from 165 MPs, while [[Andrea Leadsom]] received 66 votes and Gove trailed with 48.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news |title=Conservative leadership election: poopooed to the Cabinet following the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] as [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment Secretary]].</ref>\n\nGove was eliminated in the second ballot after receiving 46 votes, compared to 199 for [[Theresa May]]  and 84 for [[Andrea Leadsom]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/live/uk-politics-36570120|title=Michael Gove knocked out of Conservative leadership ballot|work=BBC News|accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref> He subsequently told the media that he was \"naturally disappointed\" and described his two opponents as \"formidable politicians\", welcoming the fact that the next PM would be female. He also encouraged a \"civilised, inclusive, positive and optimistic debate\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36737426|title=Theresa May v Andrea Leadsom to be next prime minister|date=7 July 2016|work=BBC News|accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs (2017\u20132019) ===\nIn May 2016, Gove voted not to reduce the permitted carbon dioxide emission rate of new homes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/11858/michael_gove/surrey_heath/divisions?policy=1030|title=Michael Gove \u2013 Environment|last=MP for Surrey Heath|first=Hansard|date=|website=TheyWorkForYou|archive-url=|archivedate=|url-status=|accessdate=27 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]], Gove was promoted to Environment Secretary by Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] during a reshuffle. Gove said he \"was quite surprised\" to be asked to join the cabinet after May sacked him in 2016 after she became Prime Minister.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jun/11/theresa-may-appoints-close-ally-damian-green-first-secretary-state|title=Michael Gove appointed environment secretary in cabinet reshuffle|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|date=11 June 2017|work=The Guardian|archive-url=|archivedate=|url-status=|accessdate=11 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter his appointment, Gove announced that a microbead ban would be put into place by the end of 2017. The ban arrived in early 2018. This meant manufacturers could no longer produce the tiny beads that are used in cosmetics and care products. Another ban came in June 2018 which stops shops from selling products that contain the beads. The reasoning behind the ban is to stop the beads harming marine life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/world-leading-microbeads-ban-comes-into-force|title=World leading microbeads ban comes into force|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=3 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 after being appointed to Secretary of Environment, Gove announced that a fuel combustion vehicle ban will be put into place due to air pollution. The ban will take effect by 2040. This ban will end the sales of new fuel combustion cars, trucks, vans, and buses that have petrol and diesel engines in the UK. The ban does not include plug-in hybrid vehicles. The reason of the ban is to reduce pollution and carbon emissions from the atmosphere in order stop the endangerment and deaths of people, animals, and plants caused by the pollution and carbon emissions. This also means that the future of transportation in the UK will be plug-in hybrid and all-electric vehicles.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-autos-idUSKBN1AB0U5|title=Electric cars win? Britain to ban new petrol and diesel cars from 2040|date=26 July 2017|work=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nHe introduced a ban on bee-harming pesticides.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/nov/09/uk-will-back-total-ban-on-bee-harming-pesticides-michael-gove-reveals|title=UK will back total ban on bee-harming pesticides, Michael Gove reveals|last=Carrington|first=Damian|date=9 November 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=27 July 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nHe was praised by [[Greenpeace UK]] executive director [[John Sauven]] for his strong stance on issues like bee-harming pesticides, single-use plastic bottles and the future of the internal combustion engine\", adding \"Gove has defied many people\u2019s expectations on the environment\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/nov/12/michael-gove-from-shy-green-to-full-throated-environmentalist|title=Michael Gove: from 'shy green' to 'full-throated environmentalist'?|last=Asthana|first=Anushka|date=12 November 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=27 July 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nGove faced criticism over the appointment of [[Ben Goldsmith]] to the role of non-executive director<ref name=gove-goldsmith-sky>{{cite news|last1=Kleinman|first1=Mark|title=Gove risks new Whitehall row over choice of DEFRA directors |url=https://news.sky.com/story/michael-gove-risks-new-whitehall-row-over-choice-of-defra-directors-11272376|accessdate=27 July 2018|work= Sky News|date=1 March 2018}}</ref> at the [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]] as Goldsmith had previously donated cash to Gove's [[Surrey Heath (UK Parliament constituency)|Surrey Heath]] constituency.<ref name=gove-goldsmith-money/> Concerns were also raised about the selection process for the job, which was overseen by [[Ian Cheshire (businessman)|Sir Ian Cheshire]], the chairman of Goldsmith's investment firm, Menhaden Capital Management.<ref name=gove-goldsmith-money>{{cite news|last1=Vaughan|first1=Richard|title=Michael Gove facing questions over appointment of Tory donor Ben Goldsmith to Defra board|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/michael-gove-questions-appointment-tory-ben-goldsmith/|accessdate=27 July 2018|work= I Newspaper|date=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn important aspect of his tenure was the introduction of laws concerning animal welfare. Animal cruelty maximum sentences increased, as did protection for animals used by government services, such as police dogs and horses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/animal-cruelty-maximum-sentences-will-be-increased-government-confirms|title=Animal cruelty maximum sentences will be increased government confirms|website=GOV.UK|accessdate=20 January 2019}}</ref> One of the \"toughest worldwide bans\" on [[ivory trade]] was also introduced in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-43620012|title=UK ivory ban to be 'toughest' in the world|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=20 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, [[Theresa May]] survived a vote of no confidence in her government, after a \"barnstorming\" speech from Gove directed towards the [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the Labour Party]], [[Jeremy Corbyn]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cityam.com/michael-gove-tears-into-jeremy-corbyn-government-defeats-no/|title=Michael Gove tears into Jeremy Corbyn as government defeats no confidence vote|date=16 January 2019|website=CityAM|language=en-GB|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref> The speech, which gained significant media attention, attacked Corbyn for his foreign policy record, with the ''[[Washington Examiner]]'' describing it as \"A tour de force. It was angry but not fanatical, passionate but not somber, and intellectual but simply put\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/opinion/michael-gove-annihilates-jeremy-corbyns-leadership-credibility|title=Michael Gove annihilates Jeremy Corbyn's leadership credibility|date=16 January 2019|website=Washington Examiner|language=en|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Gove refused to declare a climate emergency in the United Kingdom after having a meeting with [[Extinction Rebellion]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48109764|title=Climate group disappointed by Gove meeting|date=30 April 2019|work=BBC News}}</ref> Despite Gove's refusal, Parliament passed a motion to declare a climate emergency.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48126677|title=UK Parliament declares climate emergency|date=1 May 2019|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Gove argued that \"we didn't vote to leave without a deal. That wasn't the message of the campaign I helped lead. During that campaign, we said we should do a deal with the EU and be part of the network of free trade deals that covers all Europe, from Iceland to Turkey\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49165836|title=Did Raab talk about no-deal Brexit during referendum?|date=1 August 2019|access-date=3 August 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Conservative Party leadership candidate (2019)===\nOn 26 May 2019, Gove announced he would stand for the [[2019 Conservative Party leadership election|Conservative leadership]] following [[Theresa May]]'s resignation, becoming the eighth candidate to enter the contest.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tory leadership: Gove becomes eighth candidate to enter race |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48411784 |website=[[BBC]] |accessdate=26 May 2019 |date=26 May 2019}}</ref> He promised to remove the charge for UK citizenship applications from EU nationals if elected,<ref name=\"Citizens\">{{cite news |title=Gove pledges free citizenship applications |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48428261 |accessdate=28 May 2019 |agency=BBC News |date=28 May 2019}}</ref> and to replace [[Value-added tax in the United Kingdom|VAT]] with a \"simpler sales tax\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48571291 Tory leadership contest: Michael Gove 'would scrap VAT'], BBC News, 9 June 2019, accessed 10 June 2019</ref> He also planned to scrap the [[High Speed 2]] rail project and increase school funding by \u00a31 billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48699393|title=Tory MPs to choose leadership final two|date=20 June 2019|accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nBy 5 June, [[Boris Johnson]] became the clear frontrunner with the bookmakers, with Gove second favourite, followed closely by [[Jeremy Hunt]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/michael-gove-gets-boost-as-two-top-tory-women-back-him-but-odds-are-slashed-on-boris-a4159986.html|title=Gove gets leadership race boost as two top Tory women back him|date=5 June 2019|website=Evening Standard|accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref> Gove progressed following the first ballot, having received 37 votes and seen off the two women in the contest. He received 41 votes in the second ballot, and by the third ballot had 51 MPs backing him. The fourth ballot saw him gain 61 votes, moving him into second position. In the last ballot, he had 75 votes and was voted out \u2013 losing only 2 to [[Jeremy Hunt]].\n\n=== Cabinet Office (2019\u2013present) ===\n[[File:Gove meets with Bolton for Brexit.jpg|thumb|Gove with then-[[National Security Advisor (United States)|White House National Security Advisor]] [[John R. Bolton|John Bolton]] in August 2019]]\nUpon the election of [[Boris Johnson]] as Prime Minister, Gove was appointed [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]], legally representing [[the Crown]] as [[Duke of Lancaster]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/michael-gove-appointed-cabinet-office-boss/|title=Michael Gove appointed Cabinet Office boss|last=Casalicchio|first=Emilio|date=24 July 2019|website=POLITICO|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref> His otherwise [[minister without portfolio|non-portfolio]] role includes responsibility for [[no-deal Brexit]] preparations, as well as overseeing [[Department for Constitutional Affairs|constitutional affairs]], maintaining the integrity of the [[United Kingdom|Union]] and having oversight over all [[Cabinet Office]] policy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/boris-johnson-s-cabinet-feud-ends-as-gove-is-given-key-role-in-brexit-plans-pzzkcdr36|title=Boris Johnson's cabinet: Feud ends as Gove is given key role in Brexit plans|last=Wright|first=Oliver|date=25 July 2019|work=The Times|accessdate=25 July 2019|issn=0140-0460}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/michael-gove|title=The Rt Hon Michael Gove MP \u2013 GOV.UK|last=Government|first=UK|date=26 July 2019|website=United Kingdom Government|publisher=[[HM Government]]|archive-url=|archivedate=|url-status=|accessdate=27 July 2019}}</ref> Gove was excluded from a place on the [[National Security Council (United Kingdom)|National Security Council]] committee as Johnson pursued a slimming down of Cabinet operations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/07/29/no-place-michael-gove-national-security-council-boris-johnson/|title=No place for Michael Gove on National Security Council as Boris Johnson purges committees|last=Hope|first=Christopher|date=29 July 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=7 August 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> He became a central figure in the conduction of [[Operation Yellowhammer]], the civil contingency planning for the possibility of a no-deal Brexit.\n\nWriting in ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' on 28 July, Gove said that a no-deal Brexit is \"now a very real prospect\" and one that the government is \"working on the assumption of\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49141375|title=Gove: No-deal Brexit now 'assumed' by government|date=28 July 2019|accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/michael-gove-no-deal-is-a-very-real-prospect-we-must-ensure-we-are-ready-0flpkxkc3|title=Michael Gove: No-deal is a very real prospect. We must ensure we are ready|last=Gove|first=Michael|date=28 July 2019|accessdate=28 July 2019|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> He said in August that it was \"wrong and sad\" that the EU was \"refusing to negotiate\" over a new withdrawal agreement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49251257|title=Gove: EU 'refusing to negotiate' on Brexit|date=6 August 2019|access-date=6 August 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> That month, an official cabinet Yellowhammer document leaked, predicting that a no-deal Brexit would lead to food, medicine and petrol shortages. Gove said the leaked dossier outlined a \"worst-case scenario\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49388402|title=Gove: No-deal dossier is 'worst-case scenario'|date=18 August 2019|access-date=22 August 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nInterviewed on ''[[The Andrew Marr Show]]'', Gove refused to say whether the government would abide by legislation designed to stop a no-deal Brexit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49541942|title=Gove won't commit to abide by anti no-deal law|date=1 September 2019|access-date=1 September 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> A portrait of Gove was installed by the anti-Brexit campaign group [[Led by Donkeys]] on a beach in [[Redcar]], [[North Yorkshire]]. The drawing featured a quote from Gove in which he said the UK \"didn't vote to leave without a deal\" in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/01/visible-from-space-gove-portrait-appears-on-beach-in-brexit-protest|title=Gove portrait 'visible from space' appears on beach in Brexit protest|last=Media|first=P. A.|date=1 September 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=1 September 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2019 Speaker of the British House of Commons election|2019 Speaker of the House of Commons election]], Gove nominated the Labour MP [[Chris Bryant]] to replace [[John Bercow]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/11/03/labour-mp-chris-bryant-backed-senior-tories-including-michael/|title=Labour MP Chris Bryant is backed by senior Tories including Michael Gove to succeed John Bercow as Speaker|last=Hope|first=Christopher|date=3 November 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=4 November 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nGove helped to prepare Johnson for the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]] debates by playing the role of the Labour leader Jeremy Corbyn.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/19/the-itv-election-debate-your-complete-guide-to-johnson-v-corbyn|title=The ITV election debate: your complete guide to Johnson v Corbyn|last=Walker|first=Peter|last2=Waterson|first2=Jim|date=19 November 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=19 November 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> He offered to stand in for Johnson during a [[Channel 4]] debate on environmental issues but the editor of ''[[Channel 4 News]]'' said the debate was only open to party leaders.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2019-11-29/tories-clash-with-channel-4-as-michael-gove-turned-away-from-climate-debate/|title=Conservatives and Channel 4 clash after Michael Gove turned away from climate debate|date=29 November 2019|work=ITV News|access-date=1 December 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Gove took on additional responsibilities as the [[Minister for the Cabinet Office]], succeeding [[Oliver Dowden]], who had been appointed [[Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport]].{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nDuring the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]], Gove generated confusion after saying on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]'' that children with separated parents were not allowed to move between their parents' homes. He later apologised and clarified that what he said was not the case.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/michael-gove-separated-families-good-morning-britain-a4395596.html|title=Michael Gove forced to clarify lockdown rules on children with separated families after confusion|work=Evening Standard|date=24 March 2020|access-date=24 March 2020|last=Braddick|first=Imogen}}</ref> When Boris Johnson was self-isolating after having been tested positive for [[COVID-19]], Gove stood in for Johnson on from 27 March 2020 at the daily briefings of the pandemic.\n\n==Controversies==\n===Expenses claims===\n{{Main|United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal}}\nOver a five-month period between December 2005 and April 2006, Michael Gove claimed more than \u00a37,000 on a house bought with his wife [[Sarah Vine]], a journalist, in 2002. Around a third of the money was spent at [[OKA Direct|OKA]], an upmarket interior design company established by Viscountess Astor, PM [[David Cameron]]'s mother-in-law.<ref>Hope, Christopher (11 May 2009). [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5305434/Michael-Gove-flipped-homes-MPs-expenses.html \"Michael Gove 'flipped' homes: MPs' expenses\"]. ''The Daily Telegraph''. Retrieved 18 July 2014.</ref> Shortly afterwards he reportedly [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal#Areas of abuse|'flipped']] his designated second home, a property for which he claimed around \u00a313,000 to cover stamp duty.<ref name=telegraph>{{cite news |last=Hope |first=Christopher |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5305434/Michael-Gove-flipped-homes-MPs-expenses.html |title=Michael Gove 'flipped' homes: MPs' expenses |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=13 May 2009 |date=11 May 2009}}</ref> Gove also claimed for a cot mattress, despite children's items being banned under updated Commons Rules. Gove said he would repay the claim for the cot mattress, but maintained that his other claims were \"below the acceptable threshold costs for furniture\" and that moving house was necessary \"to effectively discharge my parliamentary duties\".<ref name=telegraph/> While he was moving between homes, on one occasion he stayed at the [[Pennyhill Park Hotel]] and [[Spa]] in [[Bagshot, Surrey]] following a constituency engagement, charging the taxpayer more than \u00a3500 per night's stay.<ref name=telegraph/>\n\nGove's second home was not in his constituency, but in [[Elstead]], in the [[South West Surrey (UK Parliament constituency)|South West Surrey constituency]]. Gove has sold the house and now commutes to his constituency.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wright |first=Mike |title=No base in the borough for Surrey Heath MP |url= http://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/s/2084429_no_base_in_the_borough_for_surrey_heath_mp |publisher=S&B Media |newspaper=Get Surrey |location =Guildford |date=21 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Freedom of Information and email ===\nGove has been the subject of repeated criticism for alleged attempts to avoid the provisions of the [[Freedom of Information Act 2000|Freedom of Information Act]]. The criticism surrounds Gove's use of various private email accounts to send emails that allegedly relate to his departmental responsibilities. The allegations suggest that Gove and his advisers believed they could avoid their correspondence being subject to Freedom of Information requests, as they believed that their private email accounts were not subject to the Freedom of Information Act. In September 2011, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' reported that Gove had used an undisclosed private email account \u2013 called \u2018Mrs Blurt\u2019 \u2013 to discuss government business with advisers.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ensor |first=Josie |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/8775646/Michael-Gove-faces-questions-over-use-of-private-email.html |title=Michael Gove faces questions over use of private email |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=25 August 2012 |date=20 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Vasagar |first=Jeevan |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/mar/02/michael-gove-email-private-account |newspaper=The Guardian |title=Michael Gove aides accused of deleting government correspondence | date=2 March 2012|accessdate=2 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012 the Information Commissioner ruled that because emails the ''Financial Times'' had requested contained public information they could be the subject of a Freedom of Information request and ordered the information requested by the paper to be disclosed.<ref>{{cite press release|last=Smith|first=Graham|title=Decision Notice|url=http://www.ico.gov.uk/news/latest_news/2012/~/media/documents/decisionnotices/2012/fs_50422276.ashx|publisher=Information Commissioner's Office|date=1 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306035417/http://www.ico.gov.uk/news/latest_news/2012/~/media/documents/decisionnotices/2012/fs_50422276.ashx|archivedate=6 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-17235168|title=Michael Gove loses 'private email' battle|work=BBC News|date=2 March 2012}}</ref> Gove was also advised to cease the practice of using private email accounts to conduct government business. He disputed the Information Commissioner's ruling and proceeded to tribunal, costing taxpayers \u00a312,540 in fees for legal advice,<ref>{{Cite news|last=McSmith|first=Andy|date=26 October 2012|title=Tony Blair may be an admirer of Ukrainian mills, but not on the basis of British ones he's visited|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/tony-blair-may-be-an-admirer-of-ukrainian-mills-but-not-on-the-basis-of-british-ones-hes-visited-8228721.html|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=23 February 2014}}</ref> but the appeal was withdrawn.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vasagar|first=Jeevan|title=Michael Gove appeals against ruling on misuse of email|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/mar/29/michael-gove-appeal-against-email-ruling|newspaper=The Guardian|date=29 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt was also alleged by the ''Financial Times'' that Gove and his advisors had destroyed email correspondence in order to avoid [[Freedom of Information Act 2000|Freedom of Information]] requests. The allegation was denied by Gove's department who stated that deleting email was simply part of good computer housekeeping.<ref>{{cite news|last=Henry|first=Julie|title=Michael Gove aides 'destroyed government emails'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9120506/Michael-Gove-aides-destroyed-government-emails.html|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=25 August 2012|date=3 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f70db1e0-6458-11e1-b50e-00144feabdc0|title=Gove staff destroyed government emails|last=Cook|first=Chris|date=|website=Financial Times|archive-url=|archivedate=|url-status=|accessdate=27 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== First World War centenary ===\nIn a controversial article about the [[First World War centenary]] in January 2014,<ref name=jessica>{{Cite news|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|date=4 January 2014|title= Michael Gove Attacked For 'Blackadder' Comments On 'Left-Wing' Whitewash Of WW1 History|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/01/04/michael-gove-blackadder_n_4541086.html|newspaper=[[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref> Gove criticised academic and television interpretations of World War I as \"left-wing versions of the past designed to belittle Britain and its leaders.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Perry|first1=Kerry|title=Michael Gove criticises 'Blackadder myths' about First World War|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/10548303/Michael-Gove-criticises-Blackadder-myths-about-First-World-War.html|accessdate=26 December 2015|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=3 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hunt|first1=Tristram|title= Michael Gove, using history for politicking is tawdry|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/jan/04/first-world-war-michael-gove-left-bashing-history|accessdate=26 December 2015 |newspaper=The Observer |date=4 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nSome of Gove's key points were rebuffed by the academics that Gove had used to support his thesis. Gove had criticised Cambridge professor [[Richard J. Evans|Sir Richard Evans]] saying his views were more like that of an undergraduate cynic in a [[Footlights]] review. Instead he urged people to listen to [[Margaret MacMillan]] of [[Oxford University]]. MacMillan responded, saying: \"I agree with some of what Mr Gove says, but he is mistaking myths for rival interpretations of history. I did not say, as Mr Gove suggests, that British soldiers in the First World War were consciously fighting for a western liberal order. They were just defending their homeland and fighting what they saw as German militarism.\"<ref name=toby>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jan/04/labour-gove-first-world-war-comments |title=Labour condemns Michael Gove's 'crass' comments on First World War |last1=Helm |first1= Toby |last2=Thorpe|first2= Vanessa |last3=Oltermann|first3= Philip |newspaper=The Observer |date=4 January 2014 |accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref> Evans said Gove's attack was \"ignorant\" and asked how anyone could possibly say Britons were fighting for freedom given their country's main ally was Tsarist Russia.<ref name=jon>{{cite news |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/cambridge-history-professor-hits-back-at-michael-goves-ignorant-attack-9037502.html |title=Cambridge history professor hits back at Michael Gove's 'ignorant attack' |last=Brown|first= Jonathan |newspaper=The Independent |date=3 January 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref> [[Jeremy Paxman]] said Gove had \"wilfully misquoted\" Evans on the subject of the First World War.<ref>{{Cite news |last= Plunkett |first= John |date=15 January 2014 |title= Jeremy Paxman accuses Michael Gove of 'wilfully misquoting' historian |url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/jan/15/jeremy-paxman-michael-gove |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=15 January 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Trump interview===\nIn his capacity as a writer for ''[[The Times]]'', Gove gave the first British post-election interview to [[Donald Trump]] in January 2017, along with [[Kai Diekmann]] from ''[[Bild]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gove|first1=Michael|title=Full transcript of interview with Donald Trump|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/full-transcript-of-interview-with-donald-trump-5d39sr09d|work=The Times|date=16 January 2017|accessdate=18 January 2017|url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stewart|first1=Heather|title=Michael Gove secures first post-election UK interview with Trump|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/jan/15/michael-gove-uk-interview-tory-times|work=The Guardian|date=15 January 2017|accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref> making him the second British politician to meet Trump as [[President-elect of the United States]] after [[Nigel Farage]].<ref name=\"Sharman-Indy 2016a\"/> Despite preferring [[Hillary Clinton]] to Trump as [[President of the United States]],<ref>{{cite av media|title=Newsnight|publisher=BBC News|date=16 January 2016|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b08bgfpl/newsnight-16012017|accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref> Gove's interview and consequent defence of it has been seen by some as praising the President-elect unduly,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Grace|first1=John|title=Michael Gove gorges on cheesy puff of Donald Trump interview|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/jan/16/michael-gove-cheesy-puff-donald-trump-interview|work=The Guardian|date=16 January 2017|accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref> and a photograph of Gove giving a [[Thumbs signal|\"thumbs-up\"]] to Trump was widely mocked on social media.<ref name=\"Demianyk-Huffpo 2017a\">{{cite news|last1=Demianyk|first1=Graeme|title=Michael Gove Mocked For Donald Trump Thumbs Up Photograph|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/michael-gove-donald-trump_uk_587c08dee4b04a8bfe6aaca1|work=The Huffington Post|date=16 January 2017|accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Harvey Weinstein joke===\nIn October 2017, Gove issued an apology for a joke which compared going on the ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]'' programme to [[Harvey Weinstein sexual abuse allegations|a sexual encounter with Harvey Weinstein]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Heighton|first=Luke|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/10/28/michael-gove-sparks-outrage-harvey-weinstein-joke-today-programme/|title=Michael Gove apologises after sparking outrage with Harvey Weinstein joke on Today programme|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=28 October 2017|accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-41787710|title=Michael Gove apologises for 'clumsy' Weinstein joke on Today|work=BBC News|date=28 October 2017|accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref> He was criticised by MPs of all parties who felt allegations of sexual abuse were not a suitable subject for jokes.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ruddick|first=Graham|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/oct/28/michael-gove-apologises-clumsy-harvey-weinstein-joke-today-show|title=Gove sparks outcry for Weinstein joke that 'trivialises sexual assault'|work=The Guardian|date=28 October 2017|accessdate=29 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Cocaine ===\nIn June 2019, reports emerged that Gove had taken [[cocaine]] as a journalist in his twenties.<ref name=guardian-2019-06-08>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jun/07/michael-gove-admits-to-taking-cocaine-on-several-social-occasions|title=Michael Gove admits to taking cocaine on 'several occasions'|last=Busby|first=Mattha|date=8 June 2019|work=The Guardian|accessdate=8 June 2019|last2=Gayle|first2=Damien|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=BBC-2019-06-08>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48564722|title=Gove 'deeply regrets' taking cocaine|date=8 June 2019|accessdate=8 June 2019}}</ref> Gove stated that he regretted having done so, and regarded it as having been a mistake.<ref name=guardian-2019-06-08/><ref name=BBC-2019-06-08/> In an article for ''[[The Times]]'' in December 1999, Gove argued against the legalisation of drugs, criticising members of the middle classes for their hypocrisy in doing so.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2019-06-09/gove-criticised-cocaine-users-pushing-for-legalisation-in-1999-column/|title=Gove criticised cocaine users pushing for legalisation in 1999 column|website=ITV News|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref> This was a key component of his 2019 bid to be [[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|Leader of the Conservative Party]]. In reaction, [[Craig Oliver (British journalist)|Craig Oliver]] said it would have a negative impact on his run whereas fellow candidate for leadership [[Dominic Raab]] said that he \"admires [Gove's] honesty\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jun/07/michael-gove-admits-to-taking-cocaine-on-several-social-occasions|title=Michael Gove admits to taking cocaine on 'several occasions'|last=Busby|first=Mattha|date=8 June 2019|work=The Guardian|accessdate=27 July 2019|last2=Gayle|first2=Damien|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n== Political stances ==\nGove is generally considered as combining socially liberal views \u2014 for example, on [[gay marriage]]<ref>{{cite news |title = Here's where all the Tory candidates stand on LGBT rights |url = http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2016/06/30/heres-where-all-the-tory-pm-candidates-stand-on-lgbt-rights/  |newspaper = Pink News |date = 30 June 2016 |accessdate =11 June 2017 |quote = He was one of just 29 Conservative MPs to vote in favour of Labour\u2019s Equality Act in 2007.}}</ref> \u2014 with a harder [[Euroscepticism in the United Kingdom|Eurosceptic]] and [[neoconservative]] position on foreign affairs.<ref name = \"FT interview\"/> He has expressed his view that the state should generally not interfere in domestic affairs and attests to have campaigned for economic freedom in certain matters. Gove has argued that \"the only sustainable ethical foundation for society is a belief in the innate worth and dignity of every individual.\"<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">{{Cite news | last = McSmith | first = Andy | date = 27 September 2008 | title = Michael Gove: The modest moderniser | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/michael-gove-the-modest-moderniser-944074.html | accessdate = 27 October 2013 | newspaper = [[The Independent]] }}</ref> Giving evidence before the [[Leveson Inquiry]] in May 2012, Gove said he was \"unashamedly on the side of those who say that we should think very carefully before legislation and regulation because the cry 'Something must be done' often leads to people doing something which isn't always wise.\"<ref>{{cite web |title = Michael Gove, Leveson, and the case for liberty |url = http://archbishop-cranmer.blogspot.co.uk/2012/05/michael-gove-leveson-and-case-for.html |publisher = Archbishop Cranmer |date = 30 May 2012 |accessdate = 30 May 2012 |quote = some of us believe that before the case for regulation is made, the case for liberty needs to be asserted as well. |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120602062344/http://archbishop-cranmer.blogspot.co.uk/2012/05/michael-gove-leveson-and-case-for.html |archive-date = 2 June 2012 |url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2008 Conservative Party Conference, Gove argued that [[Edmund Burke]], an 18th-century philosopher who commented on [[organic society]] and the [[French Revolution]], was the greatest [[conservative]] ever. When asked about those who believe \"Marx was right all along\", he responded that they were guilty of ignoring the systematic abuses and poverty of centrally planned economies, and criticised the historian [[Eric Hobsbawm]], saying that \"only when Hobsbawm weeps hot tears for a life spent serving an ideology of wickedness will he ever be worth listening to.\"<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/michael_gove/article5019248.ece |newspaper=The Times |title=When you're in a hole, don't dig any new ones |date=27 October 2008 |accessdate=5 April 2010 |first=Michael |last=Gove |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\n=== Capital punishment ===\nIn 1997, Gove wrote in support of bringing back hanging as [[Capital punishment in the United Kingdom|capital punishment]], which was abolished in the UK in 1965, although he has not repeated such views since. Writing in ''[[The Times]]'', Gove argued \"Were I ever alone in the dock I would not want to be arraigned before our flawed tribunals, knowing my freedom could be forfeited as a result of political pressures. I would prefer a fair trial, under the shadow of the noose.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/11595776/Michael-Gove-new-Justice-Secretary-wanted-to-bring-back-hanging.html |title=Michael Gove, new Justice Secretary, wanted to bring back hanging |newspaper=The Sunday Telegraph |date=10 May 2015 |accessdate=11 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Foreign policy ===\nThe ''Financial Times'' describes Gove as having \"strong neoconservative convictions\".<ref name = \"FT interview\"/> He proposed that the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]] would bring peace and democracy both to Iraq and the wider Middle East. In December 2008, he wrote that declarations of either victory or defeat in Iraq in 2003 were premature, and that the [[liberation of Iraq]] was a foreign policy success.\n\n{{quote|The liberation of Iraq has actually been that rarest of things \u2013 a proper British foreign policy success. Next year, while the world goes into recession, Iraq is likely to enjoy 10% GDP growth. Alone in the Arab Middle East, it is now a fully functioning democracy with a free press, properly contested elections and an independent judiciary ... Sunni and Shia contend for power in parliament, not in street battles. The ingenuity, idealism and intelligence of the Iraqi people can now find an outlet in a free society rather than being deployed, as they were for decades, simply to ensure survival in a fascist republic that stank of fear.<ref name=ScotlandOnSunday>{{cite news |url=http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/12700/Michael-Gove-Triumph-of-freedom.4812256.jp |title=Triumph of freedom over evil |first=Michael |last=Gove |newspaper=[[Scotland on Sunday]] |date=21 December 2008 |accessdate=8 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609031105/http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/12700/Michael-Gove-Triumph-of-freedom.4812256.jp |archive-date=9 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n\n[[Tariq Ali]] once recalled how, at the time of the Iraq War, he \"debat[ed] the ghastly Gove on television [... and found him] worse than most Bush apologists in the United States.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Ali |first=Tariq |authorlink=Tariq Ali |date=30 August 2013 |title=The Vassal's Revolt |url= http://www.lrb.co.uk/blog/2013/08/30/tariq-ali/the-vassals-revolt/ |newspaper=[[London Review of Books]] |accessdate=31 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, he stated that he did not believe the United States' \"current position in the world [was] analogous to that of an Imperial power, as we have come to understand imperial powers\".<ref name=\"LibInt discussion\">{{cite web|last=Gove|first=Michael|date=26 July 2003|title=Liberal Intervention: The Empire's New Clothes?|url=http://fpc.org.uk/fsblob/160.pdf|publisher=Panel discussion sponsored by the [[Foreign Policy Centre]] and [[Prospect (magazine)|Prospect]] at [[St Leonard's, Shoreditch]]|accessdate=12 February 2012|display-authors=etal|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029191250/http://fpc.org.uk/fsblob/160.pdf|archivedate=29 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe had to be calmed down by parliamentary colleagues in August 2013 after shouting, \"A disgrace, you're a disgrace!\" at various Conservative and Liberal Democrat rebels who contributed to defeating the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|coalition government]]'s motion to attack Syria in retaliation for the [[2013 Ghouta attacks]].<ref>{{Cite news|agency=[[Press Association]]|date=30 August 2013|title=Syria debate: Michael Gove brands Tory and Lib Dem rebels a disgrace|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/aug/30/syria-michael-gove-disgrace-rebels|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=30 August 2013}}</ref> He later stated he was reacting to the manner in which Labour MPs celebrated the outcome of the vote.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mason|first=Rowena|date=3 September 2013|title=Michael Gove says he was angry at Labour MPs who cheered Syria vote|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/sep/03/michael-gove-labour-mps-syria-vote|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=3 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[William Dalrymple (historian)|William Dalrymple]], reviewing Gove's book ''[[Celsius 7/7]]'' in ''[[The Times]]'', dismissed Gove's knowledge of the Middle East as being derivative and based on the views of [[Bernard Lewis]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/non-fiction/article645300.ece|newspaper=The Times|title=A global crisis of understanding|date=24 September 2006|accessdate=5 April 2010|first=William|last=Dalrymple|url-access=subscription |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070312193853/http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/non-fiction/article645300.ece|archivedate=12 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Gove cancelled a \u00a35.9 million contract to provide services for prisons in [[Saudi Arabia]], according to ''The Guardian'', because it was thought \"the British government should not be assisting a regime that uses beheadings, stoning, crucifixions and lashings as forms of punishment.\" Foreign Secretary [[Philip Hammond]] was reported{{by whom|date=October 2017}} to have accused Gove of being naive.<ref>{{cite news|last=Khomami|first=Nadia|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/oct/13/saudi-prisons-contract-gove-and-hammond-clash-over-deal|title= Saudi prisons contract: Gove and Hammond clash over deal|work=The Guardian|date=13 October 2015|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Israel and Jewish people===\nGove has described himself as \"a proud [[Zionism|Zionist]]\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejc.com/community/community-life/55213/gove-tells-ujia-i-am-a-proud-zionist|title=Gove tells UJIA: 'I am a proud Zionist'|newspaper=The Jewish Chronicle|date=22 September 2011|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref> and supports the United Jewish Israel Appeal's fundraising activities.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejc.com/galleries/the-guest-list/michael-gove-helps-raise-\u00a328m-ujia-projects|title=Michael Gove helps to raise \u00a32.8m for UJIA projects|date=10 October 2011|newspaper=The Jewish Chronicle}}</ref> In 2019, he reiterated \"One thing I have always been since I was a boy is a Zionist.\" and spoke of his desire to \"celebrate everything that Israel and the Jewish people have brought to the life of this world and hold it dear to our hearts.\" and that \"For as long as I have breath in my body and a platform on which to argue I shall be on your side, by your side and delighted and honoured to argue, powerfully I hope, on behalf of people who have contributed so powerfully to the life of this nation.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/antisemitism-has-morphed-into-hatred-of-israel-michael-tells-ujia-dinner-1.488786|title=Antisemitism has 'morphed' into hatred of Israel, Michael Gove tells UJIA dinner|last=Harpin|first=Lee|date=17 September 2019|accessdate=17 September 2019|work=The Jewish Chronicle}}</ref>\n\nGove is, like the great majority of UK Conservative Party MPs, a member of [[Conservative Friends of Israel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cfoi.co.uk/michael-gove-to-me-israel-is-an-inspiration/|title=Michael Gove: \"To me, Israel is an inspiration\"|last=By|website=CFI|accessdate=1 June 2019}}</ref> He has said that the [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions]] movement against [[Israel]] is anti-Semitic.<ref name=\"anti-semitic\"/> Gove said that jihadist terrorists \"hate Israel, and they wish to wipe out the Jewish people's home, not because of what Israel does but because of what Israel is \u2013 free, democratic, liberal and western.\"<ref name=\"anti-semitic\">{{cite news |title=Gove says boycott of Israeli goods is sign of 'resurgent antisemitism' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/sep/09/gove-against-boycotting-israeli-goods-gaza-conflict |work=The Guardian |date=9 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Health ===\nGove is one of several Conservative MPs who co-authored ''Direct Democracy: An Agenda for a New Model Party'' (2005).<ref name=Toby>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/aug/16/tory-mps-back-nhs-dismantling |title=Key Tory MPs backed call to dismantle NHS |newspaper=The Guardian |last1=Helm|first1= Toby |last2=Syal|first2= Rajeev |date=16 August 2009 |accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1491586/Additional-support.html |title= Additional support |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=8 June 2005 |accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The book says the NHS \"fails to meet public expectations\" and calls for it to be dismantled and replaced with personal health accounts.<ref name=Toby/> Gove fractured his foot in July 2015. His wife [[Sarah Vine]] inaccurately complained in her ''Daily Mail'' column that he could not have his foot X-rayed by the NHS because the minor injuries unit the couple visited did not provide the facility at weekends.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lay|first=Kat |url= http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/health/news/article4505950.ece|title=Gove can't get x-ray at weekend |newspaper=[[The Times]] |date=23 July 2015|accessdate=23 July 2015}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Jackson|first=Jasper|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/nov/20/telegraph-misled-readers-over-nhs-x-ray-service-press-watchdog-finds|title=Telegraph misled readers over NHS x-ray service, press watchdog finds|work=The Guardian|date=20 November 2015|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Religion ===\nNoting the singing of the \"deliberately anti-Catholic rant\", the [[Famine Song]] at [[Old Firm|Rangers-Celtic matches]], Gove credited Cardinal [[Keith O'Brien]] with using his intellect to protect the vulnerable in Scotland whilst regretting the absence of a similar figure in the Kirk.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/michael-gove-flabby-kirk-needs-to-regain-its-moral-might-1-1300849|title=Flabby Kirk needs to regain its moral might|last=Gove|first=Michael|date=1 November 2008|newspaper=The Scotsman|accessdate=27 October 2013|location=Edinburgh}}</ref>\n\nHe was behind plans to provide schools throughout England and Wales with a copy of the [[King James Bible]] (inscribed \"presented by the Secretary of State for Education\") to celebrate the 400th anniversary of its translation into English, though he said he backed the scheme because of the historical and cultural significance of that translation rather than on purely religious grounds.<ref name=\"Indy-kjb\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/michael-gove-defends-school-bibles-scheme-7788925.html|title=Michael Gove defends school Bibles scheme|last=Hughes|first=David|date=25 May 2012|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=27 October 2013|location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"guardiankingjames\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/jan/17/michael-gove-king-james-bible|title=And lo! Gove's Bible project did run into a spot of bother|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|date=17 January 2012|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=27 October 2013|location=London}}</ref> In April 2015, he described his faith in an article for [[The Spectator|''The Spectator'' magazine]]. In widely reported remarks, he complained that \"to call yourself a Christian in contemporary Britain is to invite pity, condescension or cool dismissal.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2015/04/in-defence-of-christianity/|title=In defence of Christianity|date=4 April 2015|work=The Spectator}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/11510368/Christianity-now-written-off-as-fixation-with-sky-pixie-Michael-Gove.html|title=Christianity now written off as fixation with 'sky pixie' \u2013 Michael Gove|last=Bingham|first=John|date=1 April 2015|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, he credited his Christian faith for his focus as Justice Minister on redemption and rehabilitation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christiantoday.com/article/michael-gove-says-his-christianity-informs-his-justice-policy-i-believe-in-redemption/77792.htm|title=Michael Gove says his Christianity informs his justice policy|work=christiantoday.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Other views ===\nGove's proposal for a new [[List of Royal Yachts of the United Kingdom|Royal Yacht]] costing \u00a360 million was made public in January 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/17/world/europe/education-minister-suggests-a-yacht-for-queen-elizabeth-ii.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |first=John F. |last=Burns |title=Education Minister Suggests a Yacht for Queen Elizabeth II |date=16 January 2012}}</ref> Deputy Prime Minister [[Nick Clegg]] criticised the idea, calling it \"a case of the haves and the have yachts\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/01/16/nick-clegg-royal-yacht-priority-list_n_1208377.html|title=Nick Clegg Says Royal Yacht Not Top Of Priority List|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=16 January 2012|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nGove believes that Scotland should remain part of the United Kingdom, arguing that Scotland's strengths complement those of other parts of the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.scotsman.com/opinion/Michael-Gove-Iceland-has-shown.4583419.jp|title=Iceland has shown up Salmond as a Darien dreamer|first=Michael|last=Gove|newspaper=[[The Scotsman]]|date=12 October 2008}}</ref>\n\nWhile deeply critical of [[Nazi Germany]] and the [[Soviet Union]], Gove believes that \"there have also been more benign empires, and in that I would include, almost pre-eminently, the [[British Empire|British]].\"<ref name=\"LibInt discussion\"/> In March 2014, he described the concentration of [[Old Etonian]]s at the top of the Conservative coalition as \"ridiculous. I don't know where you can find a similar situation in any other developed economy.\"<ref name=\"FT interview\">{{Cite news|last1=Parker|first1=George|last2=Warrell|first2=Helen|date=14 March 2014|title=How far will Michael Gove go?|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/ebe8018c-aa45-11e3-8497-00144feab7de.html|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|accessdate=14 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nGove was a member of the winning team in [[Grampian Television]]'s quiz show ''[[Top Club]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-vhYIZTtIhU|title=NEWSNIGHT: Michael Gove in 90's TV game show, real ale and real women!|last=BBC Newsnight|date=3 February 2014|publisher=YouTube}}</ref> and played the school chaplain in the 1995 family comedy ''[[A Feast at Midnight]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0109784/fullcredits#cast|title=A Feast at Midnight (1995) \u2013 Full cast and crew|website=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=27 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_auQPmnh1q8|title=Gove at Midnight|date=18 August 2012|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=9 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nGove was portrayed by actor [[Oliver Maltman]] in the 2019 [[HBO]] and [[Channel 4]] produced drama entitled ''[[Brexit: The Uncivil War]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/0/brexit-uncivil-war-review-benedict-cumberbatch-gripping-watch/|title=Brexit: The Uncivil War review: Benedict Cumberbatch is superb in this thrilling romp through the referendum|last=Bennett|first=Asa|date=28 December 2018|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=8 January 2019|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/49f2b912-0f67-11e9-acdc-4d9976f1533b|title=Vote Leave's Matthew Elliott on Channel 4's Brexit: The Uncivil War|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|author=Matthew Elliott|date=4 January 2019|quote=Screenwriter James Graham has turned the campaign into a compelling story \u2014 and nailed my mannerisms|author-link=Matthew Elliott (political strategist)}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nGove is married to journalist [[Sarah Vine]], who formerly wrote for ''[[The Times]]''<ref>{{cite web |title= Michael Gove |url= http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Gove_Michael.aspx |accessdate= 27 October 2013 |publisher= [[Conservative Party (UK)]] |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131106054026/http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Gove_Michael.aspx |archive-date= 6 November 2013 |url-status= dead }}</ref> and in 2013 became a ''[[Daily Mail]]'' columnist.<ref>{{cite news |title= Gove defends newspapers' 'right to offend' in Miliband row |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-24363765 |accessdate=27 October 2013 |work=BBC News |date=2 October 2013}}</ref> They have two children.\n\nGove is a supporter of [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers Football Club]].<ref>{{cite news |last=White |first=Michael |author-link=Michael White (journalist) |date=19 May 2014 |title=Diary: Match of the day? Wembley's all set for a Michael Gove-Jeremy Browne love-in |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/may/19/diary-michael-white-wembley-qpr-derby |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=4 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n* '''2010''': Appointment to the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom]], giving him the [[Honorific|Honorific Title]] \"[[The Right Honourable]]\" for Life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/privy-council/privy-council-members/|title=Privy Council members \u2013 Privy Council|last=|first=|date=|website=privycouncil.independent.gov.uk|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\n\nIn 2019, [[LBC]]'s [[Iain Dale]] and a \"panel of experts\" placed Gove third in a list of that year's 'Top 100 Most Influential Conservatives'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lbc.co.uk/politics/parties/conservatives/the-top-100-most-influential-conservatives-of-2019/|title=The Top 100 Most Influential Conservatives of 2019|last=Dale|first=Iain|date=30 September 2019|website=LBC|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Refbegin}}\n*''[[Celsius 7/7]]'' (London: [[Weidenfeld & Nicolson]], 2006).\n*''A Blue Tomorrow: New Visions for Modern Conservatives'' (London: Politico's, 2001; ed. with Edward Vaizey and Nicholas Boles).\n*''[http://www.bodley.ox.ac.uk/dept/scwmss/wmss/online/modern/cpa/library/pub.html#pub.C.9 The Price of Peace: an analysis of British policy in Northern Ireland]'' (London: [[Centre for Policy Studies]], 2000).\n*{{cite book|title=Unleashing Daemons. The Inside Story of Brexit.|date=2016|publisher=Hodder and Stoughton|isbn=978-1-473-65247-7|ref=harv|last1=Oliver|first1=Craig}}\n*''Michael Portillo: The Future of the Right'' (London: [[Fourth Estate (imprint)|Fourth Estate]], 1995).\n{{Refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Bennett, Owen (2019). ''Michael Gove: A Man In A Hurry''. Biteback Publishing {{ISBN|978-1785904400}}.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Michael Gove}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.michaelgove.com/ }}\n* {{IMDb name|332827}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050607063357/http://www.conservatives.com/tile.do?def=people.person.page&personID=109538 Profile] at the Conservative Party\n* John Rentoul, The Independent names Michael Gove as a [https://web.archive.org/web/20120802025913/http://www.ethosjournal.com/home/item/334-public-service-innovators top public service innovator], Ethos, June 2012\n* [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/michael_gove Column archives] in ''The Times''\n* [http://www.economist.com/node/21525379 Profile] from ''[[The Economist]]''\n* {{UK MP links | parliament = michael-gove/1571 | hansard = mr-michael-gove | hansardcurr = 4782 | guardian = 9378/michael-gove | publicwhip = Michael_Gove | theywork = michael_gove | record = Michael-Gove/Surrey-Heath/216 | bbc = 35482.stm | journalisted = michael-gove }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Nick Hawkins]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Surrey Heath (UK Parliament constituency)|Surrey Heath]]|years=[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Willetts]]|as=[[Secretary of State for Education|Shadow Secretary of State for Education and Skills]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Education|Shadow Secretary of State for Children, Schools and Families]]|years=2007\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ed Balls]]|as=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ed Balls]]|as=[[Secretary of State for Education|Secretary of State for Children, Schools and Families]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Education]]|years=2010\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nicky Morgan]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[George Young, Baron Young of Cookham|George Young]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief Whip]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Mark Harper]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Parliamentary Secretary to the Treasury]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Chris Grayling]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Justice]]|years=2015\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Elizabeth Truss|Liz Truss]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lord Chancellor|Lord High Chancellor of Great Britain]]|years=2015\u20132016}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Andrea Leadsom]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]|years=2017\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Theresa Villiers]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Lidington]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc|rows=2}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Oliver Dowden]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for the Cabinet Office]]|years=2020\u2013present}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[George Young, Baron Young of Cookham|George Young]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief Whip of the Conservative Party|Conservative Chief Whip]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mark Harper]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{Cameron Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{Cabinet of David Cameron}}\n{{First Cameron Cabinet}}\n{{Second Cameron Cabinet}}\n{{Johnson Cabinet}}\n{{Secretaries of State for Education}}\n{{Conservative Chief Whips}}\n{{Lord Chancellor}}\n{{JusticeSecretary}}\n{{Secretary of State for Environment}}\n{{Minister for the Cabinet Office}}\n{{2016 Conservative Party leadership election}}\n{{2019 Conservative Party leadership election}}\n{{South East Conservative Party MPs}}\n}}\n{{Johnson Cabinet}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gove, Michael}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]]\n[[Category:BBC newsreaders and journalists]]\n[[Category:British Christian Zionists]]\n[[Category:British Christians]]\n[[Category:British Secretaries of State for Education]]\n[[Category:British Secretaries of State for the Environment]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Critics of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Daily Mail journalists]]\n[[Category:Lord Chancellors of Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Neoconservatism]]\n[[Category:People educated at Robert Gordon's College]]\n[[Category:People from Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Oxford Union]]\n[[Category:Scottish adoptees]]\n[[Category:Scottish columnists]]\n[[Category:Scottish journalists]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for Justice]]\n[[Category:The Times people]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n", "name_user": "95.148.119.234", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Gove"}
{"title_page": "Shamil, 3rd Imam of Dagestan", "text_new": "{{Infobox royalty\n| name = Imam Shamil\n| native_name = \u015eeyx \u015eamil\n|loc_name=\u0418\u043c\u0430\u043c \u0428\u0430\u043c\u0438\u043b\n| image = Shamil by Denier.jpg\n| religion = [[Sunni]] [[Islam]] ([[Naqshbandi]])\n| succession = [[Caucasian Imamate|Imam of the Dagestan]]\n| reign = 1834 - 1859\n| predecessor =[[Gamzat-bek]]\n| successor = Overthrown by the [[Russian Empire]]\n| father = Dengau\n| mother = \n| birth_date = 26 June 1797\n| birth_place = [[Gimry]], [[Dagestan]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1871|2|4|1797|6|26}}\n| death_place = [[Medina]], [[Hejaz]], [[Ottoman Empire]] \n| place of burial = [[Jannatul Baqi]], [[Medina]], [[Hejaz]], in [[Saudi Arabia]]\n}}\n\n'''Imam Shamil''' ({{lang-en|also spelled '''Shamyl''', '''Schamil''', '''Schamyl''' or '''Shameel'''}}; {{lang-av|\u0428\u0435\u0439\u0445 \u0428\u0430\u043c\u0438\u043b}}; {{lang-tr|\u015eeyh \u015eamil}}; {{lang-ru|\u0418\u043c\u0430\u043c \u0428\u0430\u043c\u0438\u043b\u044c}}; {{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0634\u064a\u062e \u0634\u0627\u0645\u0644}}) (pronounced \"Shaamil\") (26 June 1797 \u2013 4 February 1871) was the political, military, and spiritual leader of Caucasian resistance to [[Russian Empire|Imperial Russia]] in the 1800s,<ref>{{cite book\n |title=A History of Russia\n |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofrussia00rias\n |url-access=registration\n |author=Nicholas V. Riasanovsky\n |edition= 4th\n |publisher=Oxford University Press\n |year=1984\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/historyofrussia00rias/page/389 389]\n |chapter=Chapter 29: The Reign of Alexander II, 1855-81\n}}</ref>the third [[Imam]] of the [[Caucasian Imamate]] (1840\u20131859), and a Shaykh of the [[Naqshbandi]] [[Sufi]] [[Tariqa]].<ref>[http://www.islamdag.info/story/551 The Great Shamil, Imam of Daghestan and Chechnya, Shaykh of Naqshbandi tariqah]</ref>\n\n==Family and early life==\n\nImam Shamil was born in 1797, to an [[Caucasian Avars|Avar family]].\n\nShamil was born at a time when the Russian Empire was expanding into the territories of the [[Ottoman Empire]] and [[Persian Empire|Persia]] (see [[Russo-Persian War (1804-1813)]] and [[Russo-Turkish War (1806\u20131812)]]). Many Caucasian nations united in resistance to Russian imperial aspirations in what became known as the [[Caucasian War]]. Some of the earlier leaders of [[Caucasus (geographic region)|Caucasian]] resistance were [[Sheikh Mansur]] and [[Ghazi Mollah]]. Shamil was actually childhood friends with the Mollah, and would become his disciple and counsellor.\n\nShamil had multiple wives including one of Russian and Armenian heritage named [[Anna Ivanovna Ulykhanova]] (1828-1877).<ref name=\"Barrett\">Thomas M. Barrett, ''At the Edge of Empire: The Terek Cossacks and the North Caucasus Frontier, 1700\u20131860'' (Westview Press, 1999), 193.</ref><ref>Daniel R. Brower and Edward J. Lazzerinini, eds., ''Russia's Orient: Imperial Borderlands and Peoples, 1700\u20131917'' (Indiana University Press, 1997), 92.</ref> She converted to Islam as a teenager and adopted the name \"Shuanet,\" remaining loyal to Shamil even after his capture and exile to Russia.<ref name=\"Barrett\"/> After Shamil's death in 1871, she moved to the [[Ottoman Empire]] where she was assigned a pension from the sultan.<ref name=\"Barrett\"/>\n\n== War against Russia ==\n{{main|Murid War}}\n[[File:Horschelt. Surrender of Shamil. 1863.jpg|300px|thumb|left|''Capture of Shamil'', by [[Theodor Horschelt]]]]\n[[File:Karte des Kaukasischen Isthmus - Entworfen und gezeichnet von J-Grassl - 1856.jpg|thumb|200px|''Karte des Kaukasischen Isthmus''. Entworfen und gezeichnet von J. Grassl, 1856.]]\n[[File:Imam Shamil.jpg|thumb|200px| Imam Shamil]]\n[[File:\u10e8\u10d0\u10db\u10d8\u10da\u10d8\u10e1 \u10d3\u10d0 \u10e8\u10d5\u10d8\u10da\u10d4\u10d1\u10d8\u10e1 \u10db\u10d8\u10d4\u10e0 \u10de\u10d4\u10e2\u10d4\u10e0\u10d1\u10e3\u10e0\u10d2\u10e1 \u10e9\u10d0\u10e1\u10d5\u10da\u10d0, 1859 \u10ec.jpg|thumb|right|\"Shamil's family\". Left to right: Gazi Muhammad's confident, murid Hajio; Shamil's son Muhammad-Shafi; Shamil's sons-in-law: Abdurrahim and Abdurrahman\" photo, Kaluga, 1860]]\n{{Campaignbox Caucasian War}}\nIn 1832, Ghazi Mollah died at the [[Battle of Gimry]], and Shamil was one of only two [[Murid]]s to escape, but he sustained severe wounds. During this fight he was stabbed with a bayonet. After jumping from an elevated stoop \"clean over the heads of the very line of soldiers about to fire on him.  Landing behind them, whirling his sword in his left hand he cut down three of them, but was bayoneted by the fourth, the steel plunging deep in his chest. He seized the bayonet, pulled it out of his own flesh, cut down the man, and with another superhuman leap, cleared the wall and vanished in the darkness\".<ref>Invisible armies: Blanch, sabres(\"bare\":70; \"wild beast\"; al-Qarakhi, shining (pulled out sword: 22);</ref> He went into hiding and both Russia and Murids assumed him dead. Once recovered, he emerged from hiding and rejoined the Murids, led by the second [[Imam]], [[Gamzat-bek]]. He would wage unremitting warfare on the Russians for the next quarter century and become one of the legendary guerrilla commanders of the century. When Gamzat-bek was murdered by [[Hadji Murad]] in 1834, Shamil took his place as the prime leader of the Caucasian resistance and the third Imam of the Caucasian Imamate.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1839 (June\u2013August), Shamil and his followers, numbering about 4000 men, women and children, found themselves under siege in their mountain [[fortification|stronghold]] of [[Siege of Akhoulgo|Akhoulgo]], nestled in the bend of the [[Andi Koysu]], about ten miles east of [[Gimry]]. Under the command of General [[Pavel Grabbe]], the Russian army trekked through lands devoid of supplies because of Shamil's [[scorched-earth strategy]]. The geography of the stronghold protected it from three sides, adding to the difficulty of conducting the siege. Eventually the two sides agreed to negotiate. Complying with Grabbe's demands, Shamil gave his son, Jamaldin in a sign of good faith, as a hostage. Shamil rejected Grabbe's proposal that Shamil command his forces to surrender and for him to accept exile from the region. The Russian army attacked the stronghold, after 2 days of fighting, the Russian troops had secured it. Shamil escaped the siege during the first night of the attack. Shamil's forces had been broken and many Dagestani and Chechen chieftains proclaimed loyalty to the Tsar. Shamil fled Dagestan for Chechnya. There he made quick work of extending his influence over the clans.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Ghost of Freedom|last=King|first=Charles|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2008|isbn=|location=New York, NY|pages=79\u201380}}</ref>\n\nShamil was effective at uniting the many, quarrelsome Caucasian tribes to fight against the Russians, by the force of his charisma, piety and fairness in applying Sharia law. One Russian source commented on him as \"a man of great tact and a subtle politician.\" He believed the Russian introduction of alcohol in the area corrupted traditional values. Against the large regular Russian military, Shamil made effective use of irregular and guerrilla tactics. In 1845 an 8-10,000 strong column under the command of Count Michael Vorontsov followed the Imamate's forces into the forests of Chechnya. The Imamte's forces surround the Russian column, destroying it.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gammer|first=Moshe|date=September 2013|title=Empire and Mountains: The Case of Russia and the Caucasus|url=|journal=Social Evolution & History|volume=|pages=124\u2013125|via=}}</ref>\n\nHis fortunes as a military leader rose after he was joined by Hadji Murad, who defected from the Russians in 1841 and tripled by his fighting the area under Shamil's control within a short time. Hadji Murad, who was to become the subject of [[Hadji Murat (novel)|a famous novella]] by [[Leo Tolstoy]] (1904), turned against Shamil a decade later, apparently disappointed by his failure to be anointed Shamil's successor as imam. Shamil's elder son was given that nomination, and in a secret council, Shamil had his lieutenant accused of treason and sentenced to death, on which Hadji Murad, on learning of the judgement, redefected to the Russians.<ref name=\":1\">Gary Hamburg, Thomas Sanders, Ernest Tucker (eds,),''Russian-Muslim Confrontation in the Caucasus: Alternative Visions of the conflict between Imam Shamil and the Russians, 1830-1859'', RoutledgeCurzon 2004 p\u00e8assim</ref><ref name=\":2\">[[Malise Ruthven]],'Terror:The Hidden Source,'' in [[New York Review of Books]] October 24, 2013 pp.20-24, p.20.''</ref> Though Shamil hoped the Britain, France, or the Ottoman Empire would come to his aid to drive Russia from the Caucasus, these plans never came to fruition. After the [[Crimean War]], Russia redoubled its efforts against the Imamate. Now successful, Russian forces severely reduced the Imamate's territory, and by September 1859 Shamil surrendered. Though the main theater closed, conflict in the eastern Caucasus would continue for several more years.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gammer|first=Moshe|date=September 2013|title=Empire and Mountains: The Case of Russia and the Caucasus|url=|journal=Social Evolution & History|volume=|pages=126|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Last years ==\n\nAfter his capture, Shamil was sent to [[Saint Petersburg]] to meet the [[Alexander II of Russia|Tsar Alexander II]]. Afterwards, he was exiled to [[Kaluga]], then a small town near [[Moscow]]. After several years in Kaluga he complained to the authorities about the climate and in December, 1868 Shamil received permission to move to [[Kiev]], a commercial center of the Empire's southwest. In Kiev he was afforded a mansion in [[Hrushevsky Street (Kiev)|Aleksandrovskaya Street]]. The Imperial authorities ordered the Kiev superintendent to keep Shamil under \"strict but not overly burdensome surveillance\" and allotted the city a significant sum for the needs of the exile. Shamil seemed to have liked his luxurious detainment, as well as the city; this is confirmed by the letters he sent from Kiev.<ref name=Kiev>\u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0439 \u041c\u0430\u043d\u0447\u0443\u043a, [http://pk.kiev.ua/history/2007/09/06/090007.html \u0428\u0430\u043c\u0438\u043b\u044c \u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0447\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0445\u043e\u043b\u043c\u0430\u0445] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071115004046/http://pk.kiev.ua/history/2007/09/06/090007.html |date=2007-11-15 }}, ''\"\u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u043e-\u043a\u0438\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\"'', 06.09.2007</ref>\n\nIn 1859 Shamil wrote to one of his sons: \"By the will of the Almighty, the Absolute Governor, I have fallen into the hands of unbelievers ... the Great Emperor ... has settled me here ... in a tall spacious house with carpets and all the necessities\".<ref>Pismo Shamilia Mukhammadanu, November 24, 1859, in Omarov, ed. 100 pisem Shamilia.</ref>\n\nIn 1869 he was given permission to perform the [[Hajj]] to the holy city of [[Mecca]]. He traveled first from Kiev to [[Odessa]] and then sailed to [[Istanbul]], where he was greeted by Ottoman [[Sultan Abdulaziz]]. He became a guest at the Imperial [[Topkap\u0131 Palace]] for a short while and left Istanbul on a ship reserved for him by the Sultan. In Mecca, during the pilgrimage, he met and conversed with [[Abdelkader El Djezairi]]. After completing his pilgrimage to Mecca, he died in [[Medina]] in 1871 while visiting the city, and was buried in the [[Jannatul Baqi]], a historical graveyard in Medina where many prominent personalities from Islamic history are interred. Two elder sons, ({{ill|Cemaleddin (1829-1858)|lt=Cemaleddin|ru|\u0414\u0436\u0430\u043c\u0430\u043b\u0443\u0434\u0434\u0438\u043d (\u0441\u044b\u043d \u0428\u0430\u043c\u0438\u043b\u044f)}} and [[Muhammed \u015eefi]]), whom he had to leave in Russia in order to get permission to visit Mecca, became officers in the Russian army, while two younger sons, ({{ill|Muhammed Gazi|ru|\u0413\u0430\u0437\u0438-\u041c\u0443\u0445\u0430\u043c\u043c\u0430\u0434 (\u0441\u044b\u043d \u0428\u0430\u043c\u0438\u043b\u044f)}} and [[Muhammed Kamil]]), served in the [[Ottoman Empire|Turkish]] army whilst their daughter [[Peet'mat Shamil]]  went on to marry [[Sheikh Mansur Fedorov]], an Imam who later absconded from the Russian Empire out of fear for himself and his children's life.  He fathered 11 children, one being [[John Fedorov]] who changed his name to [[John Federoff]] after migrating to Childers in Queensland, Australia<ref>http://www.genealogy.com/forum/regional/countries/topics/russia/1461/</ref> where he established a sugar cane farming empire.\n\n[[Said Shamil]], a grandson of Imam Shamil, became one of the founders of the [[Mountainous Republic of the Northern Caucasus]], which survived between 1917 and 1920 and later, in 1924, he established the \"Committee of Independence of the Caucasus\" in [[Germany]].\n\n== Musical composition ==\nAt a gathering in 1958,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.chabad.org/therebbe/article_cdo/aid/81890/jewish/A-Song.htm|title=A Song - A story of bondage and freedom portrays the mystery of life|website=www.chabad.org|language=en|access-date=2018-01-01}}</ref> the [[Menachem Mendel Schneerson|Lubavitcher Rebbe]] told a story about a great tribal leader named Shamil, who was rebelling against the persecuting Russian forces. Lured by a false peace treaty, he was captured and imprisoned. From within his prison cell, he composed a heartfelt, wordless song emoting his rise, downfall and yearn for his eventual freedom. The song was seemingly heard by a passing Hasid, who related it to his Rebbe, who in turn adapted the tune to be easily sung in the Hasidic fashion, which was then passed down in privacy through the Chabad dynasty, until the Rebbe taught it at the above-mentioned gathering. The song uncharacteristically was adopted by the [[Chabad]] movement (who usually compose their own melodies), as they take the deeper meaning of its stanzas as an analogy for the soul, which descends to a world of mortality and physicality, trapped in a body, knowing that it will one day return to its maker.<ref name=\":0\" /> (Another song uncharacteristically adapted by the [[Chabad]] movement is the tune of the [[La Marseillaise]], which was put to the tune of the prayer Ho'aderes V'hoemunah.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chabad.org/therebbe/article_cdo/aid/2465274/jewish/The-Spiritual-French-Revolution-A-Miracle-in-Our-Times-5752-1992.htm#footnote20a2465274|title=The Spiritual French Revolution: A Miracle in Our Times, 5752(1992)|website=www.chabad.org|language=en|access-date=2018-01-01}}</ref> The French government altered the tune shortly later, in 1974, only to change it back in 1981.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.marseillaise.org/english/background.html|title=La Marseillaise - background|website=www.marseillaise.org|access-date=2018-01-01}}</ref>)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* [[Grigol Robakidze]]. \"Imam Shamil\". ''Kaukasische Novellen'', Leipzig, 1932; Munich, 1979 (in German)\n* [[Lesley Blanch]]. ''The Sabres of Paradise.'' New York: Viking Press. 1960.\n* Nicholas Griffin.  ''Caucasus:  Mountain Men and Holy Wars''\n*[https://www.birmingham.ac.uk/staff/profiles/languages/gould-rebecca.aspx Rebecca Ruth Gould.] \u201c[https://hcommons.org/deposits/item/hc:21275/ Imam Shamil],\u201d Russia's People of Empire: Life Stories from Eurasia, 1500 to the Present, eds. Steve  Norris & Willard Sunderland (Bloomington, IN: Indiana University Press, 2012), 117-128. \n* [[Leo Tolstoy]]. ''[[Hadji Murat (novel)|Hadji Murat]]''\n* [[John F. Baddeley]]. The Russian conquest of the Caucasus. 1908.\n* [[Shapi Kaziev]]. [http://www.kaziev.ru/index/imam_shamil/0-44 Imam Shamil]. \"Molodaya Gvardiya\" publishers. Moscow, 2001, 2003, 2006, 2010. {{ISBN|978-5-235-03332-0}}\n* [[Shapi Kaziev]]. [[Siege of Akhoulgo|Akhoulgo]]. [[Caucasian War|Caucasian War of 19th century]]. [http://www.kaziev.ru/index/ahulgo/0-42 The historical novel. \"Epoch\", Publishing house. Makhachkala, 2008.] {{ISBN|978-5-98390-047-9}}\n* Tamar Zigman. \"[http://blog.nli.org.il/en/mendel_schneerson/ The Sufi Freedom Fighter Who Inspired the Lubavitcher Rebbe]\", [[National Library of Israel|The National Library of Israel]] website.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.chabad.org/multimedia/media_cdo/aid/140724/jewish/Shamil.htm Niggun Shamil], a [[Hasidic Judaism|Hassidic]] [[Nigun|niggun]] based on Shamil's experiences\n* [http://www.islamdag.info/story/551 The Great Shamil, Imam of Daghestan and Chechnya, Shaykh of Naqshbandi tariqah]\n* [http://www.prok.uniyar.ac.ru/img/n/11562.jpg Picture of Shamil's ''Aul'' (hideout village) in [[Dagestan]]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081011234949/http://www.coloradocollege.edu/academics/FYE/Essays/Stempf.asp Colorado College Paper]\n* [ History of Islam in Russia]\n* [http://www.kaziev.ru/photo/2-1-0-0-2 Portraits of Imam Shamil]\n* [http://www.islamdag.info Islam in Dagestan]\n* [http://www.masud.co.uk/ISLAM/misc/shamyl.htm The Jihad of Imam Shamil]\n\n===Sister projects===\n*{{commonscat-inline|Imam Shamil}}\n*{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Shamyl |short=x}}\n*{{Cite Americana|wstitle=Schamyl |short=x}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shamil, Imam}}\n[[Category:1797 births]]\n[[Category:1871 deaths]]\n[[Category:Avar people]]\n[[Category:People from Untsukulsky District]]\n[[Category:Resistance to the Russian Empire]]\n[[Category:19th-century imams]]\n[[Category:People of the Caucasian War]]\n[[Category:History of Kumyks]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox royalty\n| name = Imam Shamil\n| native_name = \u015eeyx \u015eamil\n|loc_name=\u0418\u043c\u0430\u043c \u0428\u0430\u043c\u0438\u043b\n| image = Shamil by Denier.jpg\n| religion = [[Sunni]] [[Islam]] ([[Naqshbandi]])\n| succession = [[Caucasian Imamate|Imam of the Dagestan]]\n| reign = 1834 - 1859\n| predecessor =[[Gamzat-bek]]\n| successor = Overthrown by the [[Russian Empire]]\n| father = Dengau\n| mother = \n| birth_date = 26 June 1797\n| birth_place = [[Gimry]], [[Dagestan]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1871|2|4|1797|6|26}}\n| death_place = [[Medina]], [[Hejaz]], [[Ottoman Empire]] \n| place of burial = [[Jannatul Baqi]], [[Medina]], [[Hejaz]], in [[Saudi Arabia]]\n}}\n\n'''Imam Shamil''' ({{lang-en|also spelled '''Shamyl''', '''Schamil''', '''Schamyl''' or '''Shameel'''}}; {{lang-av|\u0428\u0435\u0439\u0445 \u0428\u0430\u043c\u0438\u043b}}; {{lang-tr|\u015eeyh \u015eamil}}; {{lang-ru|\u0418\u043c\u0430\u043c \u0428\u0430\u043c\u0438\u043b\u044c}}; {{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0634\u064a\u062e \u0634\u0627\u0645\u0644}}) (pronounced \"Shaamil\") (26 June 1797 \u2013 4 February 1871) was the political, military, and spiritual leader of Caucasian resistance to Imperial Russia in the 1800s,<ref>{{cite book\n |title=A History of Russia\n |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofrussia00rias\n |url-access=registration\n |author=Nicholas V. Riasanovsky\n |edition= 4th\n |publisher=Oxford University Press\n |year=1984\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/historyofrussia00rias/page/389 389]\n |chapter=Chapter 29: The Reign of Alexander II, 1855-81\n}}</ref>the third [[Imam]] of the [[Caucasian Imamate]] (1840\u20131859), and a Shaykh of the [[Naqshbandi]] [[Sufi]] [[Tariqa]].<ref>[http://www.islamdag.info/story/551 The Great Shamil, Imam of Daghestan and Chechnya, Shaykh of Naqshbandi tariqah]</ref>\n\n==Family and early life==\n\nImam Shamil was born in 1797, to an [[Caucasian Avars|Avar family]].\n\nShamil was born at a time when the [[Russian Empire]] was expanding into the territories of the [[Ottoman Empire]] and [[Persian Empire|Persia]] (see [[Russo-Persian War (1804-1813)]] and [[Russo-Turkish War (1806\u20131812)]]). Many Caucasian nations united in resistance to Russian imperial aspirations in what became known as the [[Caucasian War]]. Some of the earlier leaders of [[Caucasus (geographic region)|Caucasian]] resistance were [[Sheikh Mansur]] and Ghazi Mollah. Shamil was actually childhood friends with the Mollah, and would become his disciple and counsellor.\n\nShamil had multiple wives including one of Russian and Armenian heritage named Anna Ivanovna Ulykhanova (1828-1877).<ref name=\"Barrett\">Thomas M. Barrett, ''At the Edge of Empire: The Terek Cossacks and the North Caucasus Frontier, 1700\u20131860'' (Westview Press, 1999), 193.</ref><ref>Daniel R. Brower and Edward J. Lazzerinini, eds., ''Russia's Orient: Imperial Borderlands and Peoples, 1700\u20131917'' (Indiana University Press, 1997), 92.</ref> She converted to Islam as a teenager and adopted the name \"Shuanet,\" remaining loyal to Shamil even after his capture and exile to Russia.<ref name=\"Barrett\"/> After Shamil's death in 1871, she moved to the [[Ottoman Empire]] where she was assigned a pension from the sultan.<ref name=\"Barrett\"/>\n\n== War against Russia ==\n{{main|Murid War}}\n[[File:Horschelt. Surrender of Shamil. 1863.jpg|300px|thumb|left|''Capture of Shamil'', by [[Theodor Horschelt]]]]\n[[File:Karte des Kaukasischen Isthmus - Entworfen und gezeichnet von J-Grassl - 1856.jpg|thumb|200px|''Karte des Kaukasischen Isthmus''. Entworfen und gezeichnet von J. Grassl, 1856.]]\n[[File:Imam Shamil.jpg|thumb|200px| Imam Shamil]]\n[[File:\u10e8\u10d0\u10db\u10d8\u10da\u10d8\u10e1 \u10d3\u10d0 \u10e8\u10d5\u10d8\u10da\u10d4\u10d1\u10d8\u10e1 \u10db\u10d8\u10d4\u10e0 \u10de\u10d4\u10e2\u10d4\u10e0\u10d1\u10e3\u10e0\u10d2\u10e1 \u10e9\u10d0\u10e1\u10d5\u10da\u10d0, 1859 \u10ec.jpg|thumb|right|\"Shamil's family\". Left to right: Gazi Muhammad's confident, murid Hajio; Shamil's son Muhammad-Shafi; Shamil's sons-in-law: Abdurrahim and Abdurrahman\" photo, Kaluga, 1860]]\n{{Campaignbox Caucasian War}}\nIn 1832, Ghazi Mollah died at the battle of Gimry, and Shamil was one of only two [[Murid]]s to escape, but he sustained severe wounds. During this fight he was stabbed with a bayonet. After jumping from an elevated stoop \"clean over the heads of the very line of soldiers about to fire on him.  Landing behind them, whirling his sword in his left hand he cut down three of them, but was bayoneted by the fourth, the steel plunging deep in his chest. He seized the bayonet, pulled it out of his own flesh, cut down the man, and with another superhuman leap, cleared the wall and vanished in the darkness\".<ref>Invisible armies: Blanch, sabres(\"bare\":70; \"wild beast\"; al-Qarakhi, shining (pulled out sword: 22);</ref> He went into hiding and both Russia and Murids assumed him dead. Once recovered, he emerged from hiding and rejoined the Murids, led by the second [[Imam]], [[Gamzat-bek]]. He would wage unremitting warfare on the Russians for the next quarter century and become one of the legendary guerrilla commanders of the century. When Gamzat-bek was murdered by [[Hadji Murad]] in 1834, Shamil took his place as the prime leader of the Caucasian resistance and the third Imam of the [[Caucasian Imamate]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1839 (June\u2013August), Shamil and his followers, numbering about 4000 men, women and children, found themselves under siege in their mountain [[fortification|stronghold]] of [[Siege of Akhoulgo|Akhoulgo]], nestled in the bend of the [[Andi Koysu]], about ten miles east of Gimry.  Under the command of General Pavel Grabbe, the Russian army trekked through lands devoid of supplies because of Shamil's scorched-earth strategy. The geography of the stronghold protected it from three sides, adding to the difficulty of conducting the siege. Eventually the two sides agreed to negotiate. Complying with Grabbe's demands, Shamil gave his son, Jamaldin in a sign of good faith, as a hostage. Shamil rejected Grabbe's proposal that Shamil command his forces to surrender and for him to accept exile from the region. The Russian army attacked the stronghold, after 2 days of fighting, the Russian troops had secured it. Shamil escaped the siege during the first night of the attack. Shamil's forces had been broken and many Dagestani and Chechen chieftains proclaimed loyalty to the Tsar. Shamil fled Dagestan for Chechnya. There he made quick work of extending his influence over the clans.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Ghost of Freedom|last=King|first=Charles|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2008|isbn=|location=New York, NY|pages=79\u201380}}</ref>\n\nShamil was effective at uniting the many, quarrelsome Caucasian tribes to fight against the Russians, by the force of his charisma, piety and fairness in applying Sharia law. One Russian source commented on him as \"a man of great tact and a subtle politician.\" He believed the Russian introduction of alcohol in the area corrupted traditional values. Against the large regular Russian military, Shamil made effective use of irregular and guerrilla tactics. In 1845 an 8-10,000 strong column under the command of Count Michael Vorontsov followed the Imamate's forces into the forests of Chechnya. The Imamte's forces surround the Russian column, destroying it.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gammer|first=Moshe|date=September 2013|title=Empire and Mountains: The Case of Russia and the Caucasus|url=|journal=Social Evolution & History|volume=|pages=124\u2013125|via=}}</ref>\n\nHis fortunes as a military leader rose after he was joined by Hadji Murad, who defected from the Russians in 1841 and tripled by his fighting the area under Shamil's control within a short time. Hadji Murad, who was to become the subject of [[Hadji Murat (novel)|a famous novella]] by Leo Tolstoy (1904), turned against Shamil a decade later, apparently disappointed by his failure to be anointed Shamil's successor as imam. Shamil's elder son was given that nomination, and in a secret council, Shamil had his lieutenant accused of treason and sentenced to death, on which Hadji Murad, on learning of the judgement, redefected to the Russians.<ref name=\":1\">Gary Hamburg, Thomas Sanders, Ernest Tucker (eds,),''Russian-Muslim Confrontation in the Caucasus: Alternative Visions of the conflict between Imam Shamil and the Russians, 1830-1859'', RoutledgeCurzon 2004 p\u00e8assim</ref><ref name=\":2\">[[Malise Ruthven]],'Terror:The Hidden Source,'' in [[New York Review of Books]] October 24, 2013 pp.20-24, p.20.''</ref> Though Shamil hoped the Britain, France, or the Ottoman Empire would come to his aid to drive Russia from the Caucasus, these plans never came to fruition. After the [[Crimean War]], Russia redoubled its efforts against the Imamate. Now successful, Russian forces severely reduced the Imamate's territory, and by September 1859 Shamil surrendered. Though the main theater closed, conflict in the eastern Caucasus would continue for several more years.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gammer|first=Moshe|date=September 2013|title=Empire and Mountains: The Case of Russia and the Caucasus|url=|journal=Social Evolution & History|volume=|pages=126|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Last years ==\n\nAfter his capture, Shamil was sent to [[Saint Petersburg]] to meet the [[Alexander II of Russia|Tsar Alexander II]]. Afterwards, he was exiled to [[Kaluga]], then a small town near [[Moscow]]. After several years in Kaluga he complained to the authorities about the climate and in December, 1868 Shamil received permission to move to [[Kiev]], a commercial center of the Empire's southwest. In Kiev he was afforded a mansion in [[Hrushevsky Street (Kiev)|Aleksandrovskaya Street]]. The Imperial authorities ordered the Kiev superintendent to keep Shamil under \"strict but not overly burdensome surveillance\" and allotted the city a significant sum for the needs of the exile. Shamil seemed to have liked his luxurious detainment, as well as the city; this is confirmed by the letters he sent from Kiev.<ref name=Kiev>\u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0439 \u041c\u0430\u043d\u0447\u0443\u043a, [http://pk.kiev.ua/history/2007/09/06/090007.html \u0428\u0430\u043c\u0438\u043b\u044c \u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0447\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0445\u043e\u043b\u043c\u0430\u0445] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071115004046/http://pk.kiev.ua/history/2007/09/06/090007.html |date=2007-11-15 }}, ''\"\u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u043e-\u043a\u0438\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\"'', 06.09.2007</ref>\n\nIn 1859 Shamil wrote to one of his sons: \"By the will of the Almighty, the Absolute Governor, I have fallen into the hands of unbelievers ... the Great Emperor ... has settled me here ... in a tall spacious house with carpets and all the necessities\".<ref>Pismo Shamilia Mukhammadanu, November 24, 1859, in Omarov, ed. 100 pisem Shamilia.</ref>\n\nIn 1869 he was given permission to perform the [[Hajj]] to the holy city of [[Mecca]]. He traveled first from Kiev to [[Odessa]] and then sailed to [[Istanbul]], where he was greeted by [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] [[Sultan Abdulaziz]]. He became a guest at the Imperial [[Topkap\u0131 Palace]] for a short while and left Istanbul on a ship reserved for him by the Sultan. In Mecca, during the pilgrimage, he met and conversed with [[Abdelkader El Djezairi]]. After completing his pilgrimage to Mecca, he died in [[Medina]] in 1871 while visiting the city, and was buried in the [[Jannatul Baqi]], a historical graveyard in Medina where many prominent personalities from Islamic history are interred. Two elder sons, ({{ill|Cemaleddin (1829-1858)|lt=Cemaleddin|ru|\u0414\u0436\u0430\u043c\u0430\u043b\u0443\u0434\u0434\u0438\u043d (\u0441\u044b\u043d \u0428\u0430\u043c\u0438\u043b\u044f)}} and [[Muhammed \u015eefi]]), whom he had to leave in Russia in order to get permission to visit Mecca, became officers in the Russian army, while two younger sons, ({{ill|Muhammed Gazi|ru|\u0413\u0430\u0437\u0438-\u041c\u0443\u0445\u0430\u043c\u043c\u0430\u0434 (\u0441\u044b\u043d \u0428\u0430\u043c\u0438\u043b\u044f)}} and [[Muhammed Kamil]]), served in the [[Ottoman Empire|Turkish]] army whilst their daughter [[Peet'mat Shamil]]  went on to marry [[Sheikh Mansur Fedorov]], an Imam who later absconded from the Russian Empire out of fear for himself and his children's life.  He fathered 11 children, one being [[John Fedorov]] who changed his name to [[John Federoff]] after migrating to Childers in Queensland, Australia<ref>http://www.genealogy.com/forum/regional/countries/topics/russia/1461/</ref> where he established a sugar cane farming empire.\n\n[[Said Shamil]], a grandson of Imam Shamil, became one of the founders of the [[Mountainous Republic of the Northern Caucasus]], which survived between 1917 and 1920 and later, in 1924, he established the \"Committee of Independence of the Caucasus\" in [[Germany]].\n\n== Musical composition ==\nAt a gathering in 1958,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.chabad.org/therebbe/article_cdo/aid/81890/jewish/A-Song.htm|title=A Song - A story of bondage and freedom portrays the mystery of life|website=www.chabad.org|language=en|access-date=2018-01-01}}</ref> the [[Menachem Mendel Schneerson|Lubavitcher Rebbe]] told a story about a great tribal leader named Shamil, who was rebelling against the persecuting Russian forces. Lured by a false peace treaty, he was captured and imprisoned. From within his prison cell, he composed a heartfelt, wordless song emoting his rise, downfall and yearn for his eventual freedom. The song was seemingly heard by a passing Hasid, who related it to his Rebbe, who in turn adapted the tune to be easily sung in the Hasidic fashion, which was then passed down in privacy through the Chabad dynasty, until the Rebbe taught it at the above-mentioned gathering. The song uncharacteristically was adopted by the [[Chabad]] movement (who usually compose their own melodies), as they take the deeper meaning of its stanzas as an analogy for the soul, which descends to a world of mortality and physicality, trapped in a body, knowing that it will one day return to its maker.<ref name=\":0\" /> (Another song uncharacteristically adapted by the [[Chabad]] movement is the tune of the [[La Marseillaise]], which was put to the tune of the prayer Ho'aderes V'hoemunah.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chabad.org/therebbe/article_cdo/aid/2465274/jewish/The-Spiritual-French-Revolution-A-Miracle-in-Our-Times-5752-1992.htm#footnote20a2465274|title=The Spiritual French Revolution: A Miracle in Our Times, 5752(1992)|website=www.chabad.org|language=en|access-date=2018-01-01}}</ref> The French government altered the tune shortly later, in 1974, only to change it back in 1981.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.marseillaise.org/english/background.html|title=La Marseillaise - background|website=www.marseillaise.org|access-date=2018-01-01}}</ref>)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* [[Grigol Robakidze]]. \"Imam Shamil\". ''Kaukasische Novellen'', Leipzig, 1932; Munich, 1979 (in German)\n* [[Lesley Blanch]]. ''The Sabres of Paradise.'' New York: Viking Press. 1960.\n* Nicholas Griffin.  ''Caucasus:  Mountain Men and Holy Wars''\n*[https://www.birmingham.ac.uk/staff/profiles/languages/gould-rebecca.aspx Rebecca Ruth Gould.] \u201c[https://hcommons.org/deposits/item/hc:21275/ Imam Shamil],\u201d Russia's People of Empire: Life Stories from Eurasia, 1500 to the Present, eds. Steve  Norris & Willard Sunderland (Bloomington, IN: Indiana University Press, 2012), 117-128. \n* [[Leo Tolstoy]]. ''[[Hadji Murat (novel)|Hadji Murat]]''\n* [[John F. Baddeley]]. The Russian conquest of the Caucasus. 1908.\n* [[Shapi Kaziev]]. [http://www.kaziev.ru/index/imam_shamil/0-44 Imam Shamil]. \"Molodaya Gvardiya\" publishers. Moscow, 2001, 2003, 2006, 2010. {{ISBN|978-5-235-03332-0}}\n* [[Shapi Kaziev]]. [[Siege of Akhoulgo|Akhoulgo]]. [[Caucasian War|Caucasian War of 19th century]]. [http://www.kaziev.ru/index/ahulgo/0-42 The historical novel. \"Epoch\", Publishing house. Makhachkala, 2008.] {{ISBN|978-5-98390-047-9}}\n* Tamar Zigman. \"[http://blog.nli.org.il/en/mendel_schneerson/ The Sufi Freedom Fighter Who Inspired the Lubavitcher Rebbe]\", [[National Library of Israel|The National Library of Israel]] website.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.chabad.org/multimedia/media_cdo/aid/140724/jewish/Shamil.htm Niggun Shamil], a [[Hasidic Judaism|Hassidic]] [[Nigun|niggun]] based on Shamil's experiences\n* [http://www.islamdag.info/story/551 The Great Shamil, Imam of Daghestan and Chechnya, Shaykh of Naqshbandi tariqah]\n* [http://www.prok.uniyar.ac.ru/img/n/11562.jpg Picture of Shamil's ''Aul'' (hideout village) in [[Dagestan]]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081011234949/http://www.coloradocollege.edu/academics/FYE/Essays/Stempf.asp Colorado College Paper]\n* [ History of Islam in Russia]\n* [http://www.kaziev.ru/photo/2-1-0-0-2 Portraits of Imam Shamil]\n* [http://www.islamdag.info Islam in Dagestan]\n* [http://www.masud.co.uk/ISLAM/misc/shamyl.htm The Jihad of Imam Shamil]\n\n===Sister projects===\n*{{commonscat-inline|Imam Shamil}}\n*{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Shamyl |short=x}}\n*{{Cite Americana|wstitle=Schamyl |short=x}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shamil, Imam}}\n[[Category:1797 births]]\n[[Category:1871 deaths]]\n[[Category:Avar people]]\n[[Category:People from Untsukulsky District]]\n[[Category:Resistance to the Russian Empire]]\n[[Category:19th-century imams]]\n[[Category:People of the Caucasian War]]\n[[Category:History of Kumyks]]\n", "name_user": "RekishiEJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shamil,_3rd_Imam_of_Dagestan"}
{"title_page": "First Doctor comic stories", "text_new": "\n\n'''First Doctor comic stories''' refers to the [[List of Doctor Who comic stories|comic strips]] devoted to the long-running British [[science fiction television]] series ''[[Doctor Who]]'', using the likeness of the [[First Doctor]] [[William Hartnell]]. The strip was launched in [[Polystyle Publications|Polystyle's]] ''[[TV Comic]]'' on 14 November 1964, less than a year after the television series began broadcasting and was the first original [[Doctor Who spin-offs|spin-off]] media from the show.<ref name=\"Scoones2012-16\">\"Scoones (2012), p. 16</ref> This strip began what has become known as the '[[Doctor Who Polystyle comic strip|Polystyle era]]': running from 1964 to 1979.<ref name=\"Scoones2012-11\">\"Scoones (2012), p. 11</ref> The First Doctor starred in this strip running parallel with his appearance on the television show, ending in December 1966, after which ''TV Comic'' began creating strips for the [[Second Doctor]]. The franchise to print a regular comic strip passed to ''[[Doctor Who Magazine]]'' (then ''Doctor Who Weekly'') in 1979, and was opened up to multiple franchises in the mid-2000s. During this time, the First Doctor has made various guest appearances as well as starring in some one-off comic strips. \n\n== Polystyle comic strips (1964-1966) ==\n\n=== History ===\n\n''TV Comic'', according to ''Doctor Who'' historian Jeremy Bentham, 'had grown up in the wake of commercial television. Just as publications like ''[[Radio Fun]]'' had blossomed during the golden years of the wireless so ''TV Comic'' began catering for young readerships who watched and liked children's programmes on [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]].<ref name=\"BenthamDWCI-15\">\"Bentham, \"Doctor Who Comics\" (March 1982), p. 15</ref> ''TV Comic'' - despite only having previously featured spin-offs of ITV programmes, decided to pitch for ''Doctor Who'' with the [[BBC]], and despite initial reticence from the channel, eventually struck a deal.<ref name=\"BenthamDWCI-16\">\"Bentham, \"Doctor Who Comics\" (March 1982), p. 16</ref> The strip launched in issue 674 with a cover date of 14 November 1964; hitting the shelves - according to ''Doctor Who'' comics historian Paul Scoones - on 8 November 1964.<ref name=\"Scoones2012-16\">\"Scoones (2012), p. 16</ref> This means that the ''Doctor Who'' comic strip in ''TV Comic'' was officially the first spin-off media from the show - the first novelization ''[[The_Daleks#In_print|Doctor Who in an exciting adventure with the Daleks]]'' not being released until later the same week on 12 November.<ref name=\"Scoones2012-16\">\"Scoones (2012), p. 16</ref> One immediate difference from the TV show was that the Doctor would be referred to in-strip as 'Doctor Who'.\n\nThere were other differences too. The rights to use ''Doctor Who'' applied 'then, as now' only applied to the likeness of the actor playing the Doctor and the TARDIS, and the portrayal of any other characters - be they companions or adversaries - would have been a separate negotiation and an increased cost, even prohibitive for companions who would appear in every installment.<ref name=\"BenthamDWCI-16\">\"Bentham, \"Doctor Who Comics\" (March 1982), p. 16</ref> Accordingly, the Doctor was given new companions in the first strip, \"The Klepton Parasites\", two grandchildren Gillian and John. Regarding ''Doctor Who'' foes, the situation was very similar. During the First Doctor period of the ''TV Comic'' strip, only the inhabitants of [[Vortis (Doctor Who)|Vortis]] from \"[[The Web Planet]]\" (1965) - the [[List_of_Doctor_Who_universe_creatures_and_aliens_(Q\u2013Z)#Zarbi|Zarbi]] and [[List_of_Doctor_Who_universe_creatures_and_aliens_(H\u2013P)#Menoptra|Menoptra]] - made it into a story. The Doctor's greatest adversaries - the [[Dalek|Daleks]] - could not appear for another reason. This was that creator ([[Terry Nation]]) had 'a separate copyright' for the creatures, and had negotiated a deal with ''[[TV Century 21]]'' (aka ''TV21'') comics around the same time for their own strip; and copyright could 'only be held by one company at any one time' for the same format.<ref name=\"BenthamDWCI-17\">\"Bentham, \"Doctor Who Comics\" (March 1982), p. 17</ref> \"[[Dalek_comic_strips,_illustrated_annuals_and_graphic_novels#Comics|The Daleks]]\" strip appeared in issue 1 of ''TV21'' (23 January 1965), and ran for one hundred and four installments, each a page long, ending in issue 104 (14 January 1967).\n\n=== Writers and Artists ===\n\nThere were three artists during the ''TV Comic'' First Doctor period. '''Neville Main''' was the first to draw the First Doctor (and thus to draw any incarnation of the Doctor).<ref name=\"Scoones2012-23-61\">\"Scoones (2012), pp. 23-61</ref> Main drew the first 9 stories (46 episodes) of the ''TVC'' strip, plus one single episode strip for the 1965 ''TVC Holiday Special'' and two single episode strips for the 1965 ''TVC Annual 1966''. '''Bill Mevin''' took over for the middle of the run, producing 7 stories (28 episodes) for ''TVC'' between October 1965 and April 1966.<ref name=\"Scoones2012-62-75\">\"Scoones (2012), pp. 62-75</ref> Although he produced no ''TVC Holiday Special'' or ''TVC Annual'' strips during this time, he returned later in 1966 to draw one of the two strips single episode strips for that year's ''TVC Annual 1967''.<ref name=\"Scoones2012-91\">\"Scoones (2012), p. 91</ref> After Mevin's relatively short tenure, the ''TVC'' strip was taken on by '''John Canning''' who produced 8 stories (36 episodes) plus two single episode strips for the 1966 ''TVC Holiday Special'' and one of the two single episode strips for the 1966 ''TVC Annual 1967''.<ref name=\"Scoones2012-77-96\">\"Scoones (2012), pp. 77-96</ref> Canning was thus the last of the three artists to draw the First Doctor for ''TVC'', and, furthermore, would go on to kick off the Second Doctor run which began late December 1966.<ref name=\"Scoones2012-100\">\"Scoones (2012), p. 100</ref>\n\nThe situation with the writers is more complex. Bentham comments: 'In those days the notion of a strip having a separate writer was strictly the prerogative of American comic books'.<ref name=\"BenthamDWCI-16\">\"Bentham, \"Doctor Who Comics\" (March 1982), p. 16</ref> Bentham describes Main's output thus: very simplistic in style, consisting of basic line illustrations drawn in a very cartoonish way. During his 45 week stint on the strip he never quite captured the likeness of Hartnell [...] He was, however, quite an inventive storywriter.<ref name=\"BenthamDWCI-16\">\"Bentham, \"Doctor Who Comics\" (March 1982), p. 16</ref>\n\n=== List of comic strips ===\n\nThe list below is of all the First Doctor comic strips that appeared in ''TV Comic'' (''TVC'') as well the yearly ''TV Comic Holiday Special'' (''TVCHS'') and ''TV Comic Annual'' (''TVCA''). The order is that designated by the publication date, as integrated by Paul Scoones.<ref name=\"Scoones2012-7\">\"Scoones (2012), p. 7</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border:none\"\n|-\n\n|style=\"background:#ebebeb\"|'''#'''{{ref label|TVC_a|a|}} ||style=\"background:#ebebeb\"|'''Title'''{{ref label|TVC_b|b|}} ||style=\"background:#ebebeb\"|'''Companions''' ||style=\"background:#ebebeb\"|'''Featuring''' ||style=\"background:#ebebeb\"|'''Pub.''' ||style=\"background:#ebebeb\"| '''Issues''' ||style=\"background:#ebebeb\"|'''Ep#''' ||style=\"background:#ebebeb\"|'''Date''' ||style=\"background:#ebebeb\"| '''Format''' ||style=\"background:#ebebeb\"| '''Writer''' || style=\"background:#ebebeb\"|'''Artist''' \n|-\n\n| 01 || \"The Klepton Parasites\" || Gillian/John || Kleptons || ''TVC'' ||674 - 683 || 10|| 14 Nov 1964 - 16 Jan 1965  || B&W || ? || Neville Main\n|-\n\n| 02 || \"The Therovian Quest\" || Gillian/John || Therovians || ''TVC'' ||684 - 689 || 6|| 23 Jan - 27 Feb 1965 || B&W || ? || Neville Main\n|-\n\n| 03 || \"The Hijackers of Thrax\" || Gillian/John || TBA || ''TVC'' ||690 -